{"title_page": "Total harmonic distortion", "text_new": "The '''total harmonic distortion''' ('''THD''' or '''THDi''') is a measurement of the [[harmonic distortion]] present in a signal and is defined as the ratio of the sum of the powers of all harmonic components to the power of the [[fundamental frequency]]. '''Distortion factor''', a closely related term, is sometimes used as a synonym.\n\nIn audio systems, lower distortion means the components in a loudspeaker, amplifier or microphone or other equipment produce a more accurate reproduction of an audio recording.\n\nIn radio communications, devices with lower THD tend to produce less unintentional interference with other electronic devices. Since harmonic distortion tends to widen the frequency spectrum of the output emissions from a device by adding signals at multiples of the input frequency, devices with high THD are less suitable in applications such as [[spectrum sharing]] and [[spectrum sensing]].<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\">[https://www.researchgate.net/publication/260672713_Analytic_Method_for_the_Computation_of_the_Total_Harmonic_Distortion_by_the_Cauchy_Method_of_Residues Iaroslav Blagouchine and Eric Moreau. ''Analytic Method for the Computation of the Total Harmonic Distortion by the Cauchy Method of Residues.'' IEEE Transactions on Communications, vol. 59, no. 9, pp. 2478\u20132491, September 2011.]</ref>\n\nIn power systems, lower THD implies lower peak currents, less heating, lower electromagnetic emissions, and less core loss in motors.<ref name=\"aspowertechnologies.com\">[https://www.aptsources.com/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/Total-Harmonic-Distortion-and-Effects-in-Electrical-Power-Systems.pdf Total Harmonic Distortion and Effects in Electrical Power Systems \u2013 Associated Power Technologies]</ref> IEEE std 519-2014  covers the recommended practice and requirements for harmonic control in electric power systems.<ref>[https://standards.ieee.org/standard/519-2014.html Recommended Practice and Requirements for Harmonic Control in Electric Power Systems]</ref>\n\n==Definitions and examples==\nTo understand a system with an input and an output, such as an audio amplifier, we start with an ideal system where the [[Transfer Function|transfer function]] is [[LTI system theory|linear and time-invariant]]. When a sinusoidal signal of frequency \u03c9 passes through a non-ideal, non-linear device, additional content is added at multiples n\u03c9 (harmonics) of the original frequency. THD is a measure of that additional signal content not present in the input signal.\n\nWhen the main performance criterion is the \u2033purity\u2033 of the original sine wave (in other words, the contribution of the original frequency with respect to its harmonics), the measurement is most commonly defined as the ratio of the RMS amplitude of a set of higher [[harmonic]] frequencies to the [[RMS amplitude]] of the first harmonic, or [[fundamental frequency|fundamental]], frequency<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\" /><ref name=\"aspowertechnologies.com\"/><ref name=\"eng.tau.ac.il\">[http://www.eng.tau.ac.il/~shmilo/10.pdf On the Definition of Total Harmonic Distortion and Its Effect on Measurement Interpretation], Doron Shmilovitz</ref><ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Slone\n  | first = G. Randy \n  | title = The audiophile's project sourcebook\n  | publisher = McGraw-Hill/TAB Electronics\n  | year = 2001\n  | isbn = 0-07-137929-0\n  | page = 10 \n  | quote = This is the ratio, usually expressed in percent, of the summation of the root mean square (RMS) voltage values for all harmonics present in the output of an audio system, as compared to the RMS voltage at the output for a pure sinewave test signal that is applied to the input of the audio system.}}\n</ref><ref>[http://www.dogstar.dantimax.dk/tubestuf/thdconv.htm THD Measurement and Conversion] \"This number indicates the RMS voltage equivalent of total harmonic distortion power, as a percentage of the total output RMS voltage.\"</ref><ref name=\"MT-003\">{{cite web\n  | title = Tutorial MT-003: Understand SINAD, ENOB, SNR, THD, THD + N, and SFDR so You Don't Get Lost in the Noise Floor\n  | first = Walt\n  | last = Kester\n  | url = http://www.analog.com/static/imported-files/tutorials/MT-003.pdf\n  | format = PDF\n  | publisher = [[Analog Devices]]\n  | accessdate = 1 April 2010}}\n</ref><ref>IEEE 519 and other standards ([http://grouper.ieee.org/groups/harmonic/single/docs/P1495D2.doc draft]): \"distortion factor: The ratio of the root-mean-square of the harmonic content to the root-mean-square\nvalue of the fundamental quantity, often expressed as a percent of the fundamental. Also referred to as total harmonic distortion.\"</ref><ref>[http://static.schneider-electric.us/assets/consultingengineer/appguidedocs/section11_0307.pdf Section 11: Power Quality Considerations Bill Brown, P.E., Square D Engineering Services]</ref>\n:<math>\n\\mathrm{THD_F} \\,= \\,\\frac{ \\sqrt{V_2^2 + V_3^2 + V_4^2 + \\cdots} }{V_1}\n</math>\nwhere ''V<sub>n</sub>'' is the RMS voltage of the ''n''th harmonic and ''n''&nbsp;=&nbsp;1 is the fundamental frequency.\n\nIn practice, the THD<sub>F</sub> is commonly used in audio distortion specifications (percentage THD); however, THD is a non-standardized specification and the results between manufacturers are not easily comparable. Since individual harmonic amplitudes are measured, it is required that the manufacturer disclose the test signal frequency range, level and gain conditions, and number of measurements taken. It is possible to measure the full 20\u201320&nbsp;kHz range using a sweep (though distortion for a fundamental above 10&nbsp;kHz is inaudible).\n\nMeasurements for calculating the THD are made at the output of a device under specified conditions. The THD is usually expressed in [[percent]] or in [[Decibel|dB]] relative to the fundamental as distortion attenuation.\n\nA variant definition uses the fundamental plus harmonics as the reference, though usage is discouraged:<ref name=\"eng.tau.ac.il\"/><ref>[http://www.icrepq.com/pdfs/BAPTISTA317.pdf VOLTAGE WAVE QUALITY IN LOW VOLTAGE POWER SYSTEMS Jos\u00e9 M. R. Baptista, Manuel R. Cordeiro, and A. Machado e Moura]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=xxbvM40Wwa8C&dq=thdf+thdr&source=gbs_navlinks_s The Power Electronics Handbook] edited by Timothy L. Skvarenina \"This definition is used by the Canadian Standards Association and the IEC\"</ref>\n\n:<math>\n\\mathrm{THD_R} \\,=\\,\n\\frac{ \\sqrt{V_2^2 + V_3^2 + V_4^2 + \\cdots} }{\\sqrt{V_1^2 + V_2^2 + V_3^2 + \\cdots}}\\,\n= \\,\\frac{\\mathrm{THD_F}}{\\sqrt{1 + \\mathrm{THD}^2_\\mathrm{F}}}\n</math>\nThese can be distinguished as '''THD<sub>F</sub>''' (for \"fundamental\"), and '''THD<sub>R</sub>''' (for \"root mean square\").<ref>[http://panelmeters.weschler.com/Asset/AEMC-605-UserManual.pdf AEMC 605 User Manual] \"THDf: Total harmonic distortion with respect to the fundamental. THDr: Total harmonic distortion with respect to the true RMS value of the signal.\"</ref><ref>[http://www.atecorp.com/ATECorp/media/pdfs/data-sheets/Fluke-39-41B_Datasheet.pdf 39/41B Power Meter Glossary]</ref>  THD<sub>R</sub> cannot exceed 100%.  At low distortion levels, the difference between the two calculation methods is negligible.  For instance, a signal with THD<sub>F</sub> of 10% has a very similar THD<sub>R</sub> of 9.95%.  However, at higher distortion levels the discrepancy becomes large.  For instance, a signal with THD<sub>F</sub> 266% has a THD<sub>R</sub> of 94%.<ref name=\"eng.tau.ac.il\"/> A pure [[square wave]] with infinite harmonics has THD<sub>F</sub> of 48.3%,<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\" /><ref>[http://www.eletrica.ufpr.br/edu/artigos/TeD2004_artigo282.pdf Total Harmonic Distortion Calculation by Filtering for Power Quality Monitoring]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_LhFxN7sUXEC&lpg=PA178&ots=ovMKpXD1QA&dq=43.5%20%22square%20wave%22%20THD&pg=PA178#v=onepage&q=43.5%20%22square%20wave%22%20THD&f=false Electric Machines By Charles A. Gross]</ref> or THD<sub>R</sub> of 43.5%.<ref>[http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=sqrt%28%281%2F3%29^2%2B%281%2F5%29^2%2B%281%2F7%29^2%2B%281%2F9%29^2%2B...%29%2Fsqrt%281^2+%2B+%281%2F3%29^2%2B%281%2F5%29^2%2B%281%2F7%29^2%2B%281%2F9%29^2%2B...%29+in+percent Calculation of harmonic amplitude sum]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120911204258/http://vk1od.net/measurement/SquareWave/THD.htm Total Harmonic Distortion of a square wave]</ref>\n\nSome use the term \"distortion factor\" as a synonym for THD<sub>R</sub>,<ref>[http://www.amplifier.cd/Tutorial/Klirrfaktor/distortion_factor.htm Distortion factor]</ref> while others use it as a synonym for THD<sub>F</sub>.<ref>IEEE 519</ref><ref>[http://energylogix.ca/harmonics_and_ieee.pdf Harmonics and IEEE 519]</ref>\n\nThe IEC defines the term \"total harmonic factor\" as :<math> d = \\frac{ \\sqrt{E^2_\\mathrm{eff} - E^2_\\mathrm{eff\\,1}}}{E_\\mathrm{eff}}.</math><ref>http://www.electropedia.org/iev/iev.nsf/display?openform&ievref=103-07-32</ref>\n\n==THD+N==\n'''THD+N''' means total harmonic distortion plus noise. This measurement is much more common and more comparable between devices. It is usually measured by inputting a [[sine wave]], [[notch filter]]ing the output, and comparing the ratio between the output signal with and without the sine wave:<ref>[http://www.rane.com/note145.html Rane audio's definition of both THD and THD+N]</ref>\n:<math>\n\\mathrm{THD\\!\\!+\\!\\!N} = \\frac{\\displaystyle\\sum_{n=2}^\\infty{\\text{harmonics}} + \\text{noise}}{\\text{fundamental}}\n</math>\n\nLike the THD measurement, this is a ratio of RMS amplitudes,<ref name=\"MT-003\"/><ref>[http://www.analog.com/static/imported-files/tutorials/MT-053.pdf Op Amp Distortion: HD, THD, THD + N, IMD, SFDR, MTPR]</ref> and can be measured as THD<sub>F</sub> (bandpassed or calculated fundamental as the denominator) or, more commonly, as THD<sub>R</sub> (total distorted signal as the denominator).  Audio Precision measurements are THD<sub>R</sub>, for instance.<ref>[http://www.ap.com/solutions/introtoaudiotest/thd+n Introduction to the Basic Six Audio Tests] \"Since the sum of the distortion products will always be less than the total signal, the THD+N Ratio will always be a negative decibel value, or a percent value less than 100%.\"</ref>\n\nA meaningful measurement must include the [[Bandwidth (signal processing)|bandwidth]] of measurement. This measurement includes effects from [[Ground loop (electricity)|ground loop]] power line hum, high-frequency interference, [[intermodulation distortion]] between these tones and the fundamental, and so on, in addition to harmonic distortion. For psychoacoustic measurements, a weighting curve is applied such as [[A-weighting]] or [[ITU-R BS.468]], which is intended to accentuate what is most audible to the human ear, contributing to a more accurate measurement.\n\nFor a given input frequency and amplitude, THD+N is reciprocal to [[SINAD]], provided that both measurements are made over the same bandwidth.\n\n==Measurement==\nThe distortion of a [[waveform]] relative to a pure sinewave can be measured either by using a [[THD analyzer]] to [[Fourier analysis|analyse the output wave into its constituent harmonics]] and noting the amplitude of each relative to the fundamental; or by cancelling out the fundamental with a [[notch filter]] and measuring the remaining signal, which will be total aggregate harmonic distortion plus noise.\n\nGiven a sinewave generator of very low inherent distortion, it can be used as input to amplification equipment, whose distortion at different frequencies and signal levels can be measured by examining the output waveform.\n\nThere is electronic equipment both to generate sinewaves and to measure distortion; but a general-purpose [[digital computer]] equipped with a [[sound card]] can carry out harmonic analysis with suitable software. Different software can be used to generate sinewaves, but the inherent distortion may be too high for measurement of very low-distortion amplifiers.\n\n=== Interpretation ===\nFor many purposes different types of harmonics are not equivalent.  For instance, crossover distortion at a given THD is much more audible than clipping distortion at the same THD, since the harmonics produced are at higher frequencies, which are not as easily [[Auditory masking|masked]] by the fundamental.<ref>[http://sound.whsites.net/valves/valve-trans.html#s33 Distortion \u2013 Valves vs. Transistors]</ref>  A single THD number is inadequate to specify audibility, and must be interpreted with care.  Taking THD measurements at different output levels would expose whether the distortion is clipping (which increases with level) or crossover (which decreases with level).\n\nTHD is an average of a number of harmonics equally weighted, even though research performed decades ago identifies that lower order harmonics are harder to hear at the same level, compared with higher order ones. In addition, even order harmonics are said to be generally harder to hear than odd order.<ref>[https://www.gearslutz.com/board/so-much-gear-so-little-time/382595-odd-vs-even-harmonic-distortion.html]</ref> A number of formulas that attempt to correlate THD with actual audibility have been published, however none have gained mainstream use.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n==Examples==\nFor many standard signals, the above criterion may be calculated analytically in a closed form.<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\" /> For example, a pure [[square wave]] has THD<sub>F</sub> equal to\n:<math>\n\\mathrm{THD_F} \\,= \\,\\sqrt{\\frac{\\,\\pi^2}{8}-1\\,}\\approx \\, 0.483\\,=\\,48.3\\%\n</math>\nThe [[Sawtooth wave|sawtooth signal]] possesses\n:<math>\n\\mathrm{THD_F} \\,= \\,\\sqrt{\\frac{\\,\\pi^2}{6}-1\\,}\\approx \\, 0.803\\,=\\,80.3\\%\n</math>\nThe pure symmetrical [[triangle wave]] has THD<sub>F</sub> of \n:<math>\n\\mathrm{THD_F} \\,= \\,\\sqrt{\\frac{\\,\\pi^4}{96}-1\\,}\\approx\\,0.121\\,= \\, 12.1\\%\n</math>\nFor the rectangular [[pulse train]] with the ''[[duty cycle]]'' ''\u03bc'' (called sometimes the ''cyclic ratio''),\nthe THD<sub>F</sub> has the form\n: <math> \n\\mathrm{THD_F}\\,(\\mu)=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\mu(1-\\mu)\\pi^2\\,}{2\\sin^2\\pi\\mu}-1\\;}\\,,\\qquad 0<\\mu<1\n</math>\nand logically, reaches the minimum (\u22480.483) when the signal becomes symmetrical ''\u03bc''=0.5, ''i.e.'' the pure [[square wave]].<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\" /> Appropriate filtering of these signals may drastically reduce the resulting THD. For instance, the pure [[square wave]] filtered by the [[Butterworth filter|Butterworth low-pass filter]] of the second-order (with the [[cutoff frequency]] set equal to the fundamental frequency) has THD<sub>F</sub> of 5.3%, while the same signal filtered by the fourth-order filter has THD<sub>F</sub> of 0.6%.<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\" /> However, analytic computation of the THD<sub>F</sub> for complicated waveforms and filters often represents a difficult task, and the resulting expressions may be quite laborious to obtain. For example, the closed-form expression for the THD<sub>F</sub> of the [[sawtooth wave]] filtered by the first-order [[Butterworth filter|Butterworth low-pass filter]] is simply\n:<math>\n\\mathrm{THD_F}\\,= \\,\n\\sqrt{\\frac{\\,\\pi^2}{3} - \\pi\\coth\\pi\\,}\\,\\approx\\,0.370\\,= \\, 37.0\\%\n</math>\nwhile that for the same signal filtered by the second-order [[Butterworth filter]] is given by \na rather cumbersome formula<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\" />\n: <math> \n\\mathrm{THD_F}\\,=\n\\sqrt{\\pi\\,\\frac{\\;\n\\cot\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}}\\cdot\\coth^{2\\!}\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}}\n-\\cot^{2\\!}\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}}\\cdot\\coth\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}}\n-\\cot\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}} - \\coth\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}}\\;}\n{\\sqrt{2\\,}\\left(\\!\\cot^{2\\!}\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}}\n+\\coth^{2\\!}\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}}\\!\\right)}\n\\,+\\,\\frac{\\,\\pi^2}{3} \\,-\\, 1\\;} \n\\;\\approx\\;0.181\\,= \\, 18.1\\%\n</math>\nYet, the closed-form expression for the THD<sub>F</sub> of the [[pulse train]] filtered by the ''p''th-order [[Butterworth filter|Butterworth low-pass filter]] is even more complicated and has the following form\n: <math> \n\\mathrm{THD_F}\\,(\\mu, p)= \\csc\\pi\\mu\\,\\cdot \\!\\sqrt{\\mu(1-\\mu)\\pi^2-\\,\\sin^2\\!\\pi\\mu\\,\n-\\,\\frac{\\,\\pi}{2}\\sum_{s=1}^{2p} \\frac{\\cot \\pi z_s}{z_s^2} \n\\prod\\limits_{\\scriptstyle l=1\\atop\\scriptstyle l\\neq s}^{2p}\\!\\frac{1}{\\,z_s-z_l\\,}\\,\n+\\,\\frac{\\,\\pi}{2}\\,\\mathrm{Re}\\sum_{s=1}^{2p} \\frac{e^{i\\pi z_s(2\\mu-1)}}{z_s^2\\sin \\pi z_s} \n\\prod\\limits_{\\scriptstyle l=1\\atop\\scriptstyle l\\neq s}^{2p}\\!\\frac{1}{\\,z_s-z_l\\,}\\,}\n</math>\nwhere ''\u03bc'' is the [[duty cycle]], 0<''\u03bc''<1,  and \n: <math> \nz_l\\equiv \\exp{\\frac{i\\pi(2l-1)}{2p}}\\,, \\qquad l=1, 2,\\ldots, 2p \n</math>\nsee<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\" /> for more details.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Audio system measurements]]\n* [[Signal-to-noise ratio]]\n* [[Timbre]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sengpielaudio.com/calculator-thd.htm Conversion: Distortion attenuation in dB to distortion factor THD in %]\n* [http://www.rohde-schwarz.com/appnote/1GA56 Swept Harmonic Distortion Measurements]\n* [http://www.rohde-schwarz.com/appnote/1GA55 Harmonic Distortion Measurements in the Presence of Noise]\n\n[[Category:Electrical parameters]]\n[[Category:Audio amplifier specifications]]\n", "text_old": "The '''total harmonic distortion''' ('''THD''' or '''THDi''') is a measurement of the [[harmonic distortion]] present in a signal and is defined as the ratio of the sum of the powers of all harmonic components to the power of the [[fundamental frequency]]. '''Distortion factor''', a closely related term, is sometimes used as a synonym.\n\nIn audio systems, lower distortion means the components in a loudspeaker, amplifier or microphone or other equipment produce a more accurate reproduction of an audio recording.\n\nIn radio communications, devices with lower THD tend to produce less unintentional interference with other electronic devices. Since harmonic distortion tends to widen the frequency spectrum of the output emissions from a device by adding signals at multiples of the input frequency, devices with high THD are less suitable in applications such as [[spectrum sharing]] and [[spectrum sensing]].<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\">[https://www.researchgate.net/publication/260672713_Analytic_Method_for_the_Computation_of_the_Total_Harmonic_Distortion_by_the_Cauchy_Method_of_Residues Iaroslav Blagouchine and Eric Moreau. ''Analytic Method for the Computation of the Total Harmonic Distortion by the Cauchy Method of Residues.'' IEEE Transactions on Communications, vol. 59, no. 9, pp. 2478\u20132491, September 2011.]</ref>\n\nIn power systems, lower THD implies lower peak currents, less heating, lower electromagnetic emissions, and less core loss in motors.<ref name=\"aspowertechnologies.com\">[https://www.aptsources.com/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/Total-Harmonic-Distortion-and-Effects-in-Electrical-Power-Systems.pdf Total Harmonic Distortion and Effects in Electrical Power Systems \u2013 Associated Power Technologies]</ref> IEEE std 519-2014  covers the recommended practice and requirements for harmonic control in electric power systems.<ref>[https://standards.ieee.org/standard/519-2014.html Recommended Practice and Requirements for Harmonic Control in Electric Power Systems]</ref>\n\n==Definitions and examples==\nTo understand a system with an input and an output, such as an audio amplifier, we start with an ideal system where the [[Transfer Function|transfer function]] is [[LTI system theory|linear and time-invariant]]. When a sinusoidal signal of frequency \u03c9 passes through a non-ideal, non-linear device, additional content is added at multiples n\u03c9 (harmonics) of the original frequency. THD is a measure of that additional signal content not present in the input signal.\n\nWhen the main performance criterion is the \u2033purity\u2033 of the original sine wave (in other words, the contribution of the original frequency with respect to its harmonics), the measurement is most commonly defined as the ratio of the RMS amplitude of a set of higher [[harmonic]] frequencies to the [[RMS amplitude]] of the first harmonic, or [[fundamental frequency|fundamental]], frequency<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\" /><ref name=\"aspowertechnologies.com\"/><ref name=\"eng.tau.ac.il\">[http://www.eng.tau.ac.il/~shmilo/10.pdf On the Definition of Total Harmonic Distortion and Its Effect on Measurement Interpretation], Doron Shmilovitz</ref><ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Slone\n  | first = G. Randy \n  | title = The audiophile's project sourcebook\n  | publisher = McGraw-Hill/TAB Electronics\n  | year = 2001\n  | isbn = 0-07-137929-0\n  | page = 10 \n  | quote = This is the ratio, usually expressed in percent, of the summation of the root mean square (RMS) voltage values for all harmonics present in the output of an audio system, as compared to the RMS voltage at the output for a pure sinewave test signal that is applied to the input of the audio system.}}\n</ref><ref>[http://www.dogstar.dantimax.dk/tubestuf/thdconv.htm THD Measurement and Conversion] \"This number indicates the RMS voltage equivalent of total harmonic distortion power, as a percentage of the total output RMS voltage.\"</ref><ref name=\"MT-003\">{{cite web\n  | title = Tutorial MT-003: Understand SINAD, ENOB, SNR, THD, THD + N, and SFDR so You Don't Get Lost in the Noise Floor\n  | first = Walt\n  | last = Kester\n  | url = http://www.analog.com/static/imported-files/tutorials/MT-003.pdf\n  | format = PDF\n  | publisher = [[Analog Devices]]\n  | accessdate = 1 April 2010}}\n</ref><ref>IEEE 519 and other standards ([http://grouper.ieee.org/groups/harmonic/single/docs/P1495D2.doc draft]): \"distortion factor: The ratio of the root-mean-square of the harmonic content to the root-mean-square\nvalue of the fundamental quantity, often expressed as a percent of the fundamental. Also referred to as total harmonic distortion.\"</ref><ref>[http://static.schneider-electric.us/assets/consultingengineer/appguidedocs/section11_0307.pdf Section 11: Power Quality Considerations Bill Brown, P.E., Square D Engineering Services]</ref>\n:<math>\n\\mathrm{THD_F} \\,= \\,\\frac{ \\sqrt{V_2^2 + V_3^2 + V_4^2 + \\cdots} }{V_1}\n</math>\nwhere ''V<sub>n</sub>'' is the RMS voltage of the ''n''th harmonic and ''n''&nbsp;=&nbsp;1 is the fundamental frequency.\n\nIn practice, the THD<sub>F</sub> is commonly used in audio distortion specifications (percentage THD); however, THD is a non-standardized specification and the results between manufacturers are not easily comparable. Since individual harmonic amplitudes are measured, it is required that the manufacturer disclose the test signal frequency range, level and gain conditions, and number of measurements taken. It is possible to measure the full 20\u201320&nbsp;kHz range using a sweep (though distortion for a fundamental above 10&nbsp;kHz is inaudible).\n\nMeasurements for calculating the THD are made at the output of a device under specified conditions. The THD is usually expressed in [[percent]] or in [[Decibel|dB]] relative to the fundamental as distortion attenuation.\n\nA variant definition uses the fundamental plus harmonics as the reference, though usage is discouraged:<ref name=\"eng.tau.ac.il\"/><ref>[http://www.icrepq.com/pdfs/BAPTISTA317.pdf VOLTAGE WAVE QUALITY IN LOW VOLTAGE POWER SYSTEMS Jos\u00e9 M. R. Baptista, Manuel R. Cordeiro, and A. Machado e Moura]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=xxbvM40Wwa8C&dq=thdf+thdr&source=gbs_navlinks_s The Power Electronics Handbook] edited by Timothy L. Skvarenina \"This definition is used by the Canadian Standards Association and the IEC\"</ref>\n\n:<math>\n\\mathrm{THD_R} \\,=\\,\n\\frac{ \\sqrt{V_2^2 + V_3^2 + V_4^2 + \\cdots} }{\\sqrt{V_1^2 + V_2^2 + V_3^2 + \\cdots}}\\,\n= \\,\\frac{\\mathrm{THD_F}}{\\sqrt{1 + \\mathrm{THD}^2_\\mathrm{F}}}\n</math>\nThese can be distinguished as '''THD<sub>F</sub>''' (for \"fundamental\"), and '''THD<sub>R</sub>''' (for \"root mean square\").<ref>[http://panelmeters.weschler.com/Asset/AEMC-605-UserManual.pdf AEMC 605 User Manual] \"THDf: Total harmonic distortion with respect to the fundamental. THDr: Total harmonic distortion with respect to the true RMS value of the signal.\"</ref><ref>[http://www.atecorp.com/ATECorp/media/pdfs/data-sheets/Fluke-39-41B_Datasheet.pdf 39/41B Power Meter Glossary]</ref>  THD<sub>R</sub> cannot exceed 100%.  At low distortion levels, the difference between the two calculation methods is negligible.  For instance, a signal with THD<sub>F</sub> of 10% has a very similar THD<sub>R</sub> of 9.95%.  However, at higher distortion levels the discrepancy becomes large.  For instance, a signal with THD<sub>F</sub> 266% has a THD<sub>R</sub> of 94%.<ref name=\"eng.tau.ac.il\"/> A pure [[square wave]] with infinite harmonics has THD<sub>F</sub> of 48.3%,<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\" /><ref>[http://www.eletrica.ufpr.br/edu/artigos/TeD2004_artigo282.pdf Total Harmonic Distortion Calculation by Filtering for Power Quality Monitoring]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_LhFxN7sUXEC&lpg=PA178&ots=ovMKpXD1QA&dq=43.5%20%22square%20wave%22%20THD&pg=PA178#v=onepage&q=43.5%20%22square%20wave%22%20THD&f=false Electric Machines By Charles A. Gross]</ref> or THD<sub>R</sub> of 43.5%.<ref>[http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=sqrt%28%281%2F3%29^2%2B%281%2F5%29^2%2B%281%2F7%29^2%2B%281%2F9%29^2%2B...%29%2Fsqrt%281^2+%2B+%281%2F3%29^2%2B%281%2F5%29^2%2B%281%2F7%29^2%2B%281%2F9%29^2%2B...%29+in+percent Calculation of harmonic amplitude sum]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120911204258/http://vk1od.net/measurement/SquareWave/THD.htm Total Harmonic Distortion of a square wave]</ref>\n\nSome use the term \"distortion factor\" as a synonym for THD<sub>R</sub>,<ref>[http://www.amplifier.cd/Tutorial/Klirrfaktor/distortion_factor.htm Distortion factor]</ref> while others use it as a synonym for THD<sub>F</sub>.<ref>IEEE 519</ref><ref>[http://energylogix.ca/harmonics_and_ieee.pdf Harmonics and IEEE 519]</ref>\n\n==THD+N==\n'''THD+N''' means total harmonic distortion plus noise. This measurement is much more common and more comparable between devices. It is usually measured by inputting a [[sine wave]], [[notch filter]]ing the output, and comparing the ratio between the output signal with and without the sine wave:<ref>[http://www.rane.com/note145.html Rane audio's definition of both THD and THD+N]</ref>\n:<math>\n\\mathrm{THD\\!\\!+\\!\\!N} = \\frac{\\displaystyle\\sum_{n=2}^\\infty{\\text{harmonics}} + \\text{noise}}{\\text{fundamental}}\n</math>\n\nLike the THD measurement, this is a ratio of RMS amplitudes,<ref name=\"MT-003\"/><ref>[http://www.analog.com/static/imported-files/tutorials/MT-053.pdf Op Amp Distortion: HD, THD, THD + N, IMD, SFDR, MTPR]</ref> and can be measured as THD<sub>F</sub> (bandpassed or calculated fundamental as the denominator) or, more commonly, as THD<sub>R</sub> (total distorted signal as the denominator).  Audio Precision measurements are THD<sub>R</sub>, for instance.<ref>[http://www.ap.com/solutions/introtoaudiotest/thd+n Introduction to the Basic Six Audio Tests] \"Since the sum of the distortion products will always be less than the total signal, the THD+N Ratio will always be a negative decibel value, or a percent value less than 100%.\"</ref>\n\nA meaningful measurement must include the [[Bandwidth (signal processing)|bandwidth]] of measurement. This measurement includes effects from [[Ground loop (electricity)|ground loop]] power line hum, high-frequency interference, [[intermodulation distortion]] between these tones and the fundamental, and so on, in addition to harmonic distortion. For psychoacoustic measurements, a weighting curve is applied such as [[A-weighting]] or [[ITU-R BS.468]], which is intended to accentuate what is most audible to the human ear, contributing to a more accurate measurement.\n\nFor a given input frequency and amplitude, THD+N is reciprocal to [[SINAD]], provided that both measurements are made over the same bandwidth.\n\n==Measurement==\nThe distortion of a [[waveform]] relative to a pure sinewave can be measured either by using a [[THD analyzer]] to [[Fourier analysis|analyse the output wave into its constituent harmonics]] and noting the amplitude of each relative to the fundamental; or by cancelling out the fundamental with a [[notch filter]] and measuring the remaining signal, which will be total aggregate harmonic distortion plus noise.\n\nGiven a sinewave generator of very low inherent distortion, it can be used as input to amplification equipment, whose distortion at different frequencies and signal levels can be measured by examining the output waveform.\n\nThere is electronic equipment both to generate sinewaves and to measure distortion; but a general-purpose [[digital computer]] equipped with a [[sound card]] can carry out harmonic analysis with suitable software. Different software can be used to generate sinewaves, but the inherent distortion may be too high for measurement of very low-distortion amplifiers.\n\n=== Interpretation ===\nFor many purposes different types of harmonics are not equivalent.  For instance, crossover distortion at a given THD is much more audible than clipping distortion at the same THD, since the harmonics produced are at higher frequencies, which are not as easily [[Auditory masking|masked]] by the fundamental.<ref>[http://sound.whsites.net/valves/valve-trans.html#s33 Distortion \u2013 Valves vs. Transistors]</ref>  A single THD number is inadequate to specify audibility, and must be interpreted with care.  Taking THD measurements at different output levels would expose whether the distortion is clipping (which increases with level) or crossover (which decreases with level).\n\nTHD is an average of a number of harmonics equally weighted, even though research performed decades ago identifies that lower order harmonics are harder to hear at the same level, compared with higher order ones. In addition, even order harmonics are said to be generally harder to hear than odd order.<ref>[https://www.gearslutz.com/board/so-much-gear-so-little-time/382595-odd-vs-even-harmonic-distortion.html]</ref> A number of formulas that attempt to correlate THD with actual audibility have been published, however none have gained mainstream use.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n==Examples==\nFor many standard signals, the above criterion may be calculated analytically in a closed form.<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\" /> For example, a pure [[square wave]] has THD<sub>F</sub> equal to\n:<math>\n\\mathrm{THD_F} \\,= \\,\\sqrt{\\frac{\\,\\pi^2}{8}-1\\,}\\approx \\, 0.483\\,=\\,48.3\\%\n</math>\nThe [[Sawtooth wave|sawtooth signal]] possesses\n:<math>\n\\mathrm{THD_F} \\,= \\,\\sqrt{\\frac{\\,\\pi^2}{6}-1\\,}\\approx \\, 0.803\\,=\\,80.3\\%\n</math>\nThe pure symmetrical [[triangle wave]] has THD<sub>F</sub> of \n:<math>\n\\mathrm{THD_F} \\,= \\,\\sqrt{\\frac{\\,\\pi^4}{96}-1\\,}\\approx\\,0.121\\,= \\, 12.1\\%\n</math>\nFor the rectangular [[pulse train]] with the ''[[duty cycle]]'' ''\u03bc'' (called sometimes the ''cyclic ratio''),\nthe THD<sub>F</sub> has the form\n: <math> \n\\mathrm{THD_F}\\,(\\mu)=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\mu(1-\\mu)\\pi^2\\,}{2\\sin^2\\pi\\mu}-1\\;}\\,,\\qquad 0<\\mu<1\n</math>\nand logically, reaches the minimum (\u22480.483) when the signal becomes symmetrical ''\u03bc''=0.5, ''i.e.'' the pure [[square wave]].<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\" /> Appropriate filtering of these signals may drastically reduce the resulting THD. For instance, the pure [[square wave]] filtered by the [[Butterworth filter|Butterworth low-pass filter]] of the second-order (with the [[cutoff frequency]] set equal to the fundamental frequency) has THD<sub>F</sub> of 5.3%, while the same signal filtered by the fourth-order filter has THD<sub>F</sub> of 0.6%.<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\" /> However, analytic computation of the THD<sub>F</sub> for complicated waveforms and filters often represents a difficult task, and the resulting expressions may be quite laborious to obtain. For example, the closed-form expression for the THD<sub>F</sub> of the [[sawtooth wave]] filtered by the first-order [[Butterworth filter|Butterworth low-pass filter]] is simply\n:<math>\n\\mathrm{THD_F}\\,= \\,\n\\sqrt{\\frac{\\,\\pi^2}{3} - \\pi\\coth\\pi\\,}\\,\\approx\\,0.370\\,= \\, 37.0\\%\n</math>\nwhile that for the same signal filtered by the second-order [[Butterworth filter]] is given by \na rather cumbersome formula<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\" />\n: <math> \n\\mathrm{THD_F}\\,=\n\\sqrt{\\pi\\,\\frac{\\;\n\\cot\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}}\\cdot\\coth^{2\\!}\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}}\n-\\cot^{2\\!}\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}}\\cdot\\coth\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}}\n-\\cot\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}} - \\coth\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}}\\;}\n{\\sqrt{2\\,}\\left(\\!\\cot^{2\\!}\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}}\n+\\coth^{2\\!}\\dfrac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2\\,}}\\!\\right)}\n\\,+\\,\\frac{\\,\\pi^2}{3} \\,-\\, 1\\;} \n\\;\\approx\\;0.181\\,= \\, 18.1\\%\n</math>\nYet, the closed-form expression for the THD<sub>F</sub> of the [[pulse train]] filtered by the ''p''th-order [[Butterworth filter|Butterworth low-pass filter]] is even more complicated and has the following form\n: <math> \n\\mathrm{THD_F}\\,(\\mu, p)= \\csc\\pi\\mu\\,\\cdot \\!\\sqrt{\\mu(1-\\mu)\\pi^2-\\,\\sin^2\\!\\pi\\mu\\,\n-\\,\\frac{\\,\\pi}{2}\\sum_{s=1}^{2p} \\frac{\\cot \\pi z_s}{z_s^2} \n\\prod\\limits_{\\scriptstyle l=1\\atop\\scriptstyle l\\neq s}^{2p}\\!\\frac{1}{\\,z_s-z_l\\,}\\,\n+\\,\\frac{\\,\\pi}{2}\\,\\mathrm{Re}\\sum_{s=1}^{2p} \\frac{e^{i\\pi z_s(2\\mu-1)}}{z_s^2\\sin \\pi z_s} \n\\prod\\limits_{\\scriptstyle l=1\\atop\\scriptstyle l\\neq s}^{2p}\\!\\frac{1}{\\,z_s-z_l\\,}\\,}\n</math>\nwhere ''\u03bc'' is the [[duty cycle]], 0<''\u03bc''<1,  and \n: <math> \nz_l\\equiv \\exp{\\frac{i\\pi(2l-1)}{2p}}\\,, \\qquad l=1, 2,\\ldots, 2p \n</math>\nsee<ref name=\"iaroslav_04\" /> for more details.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Audio system measurements]]\n* [[Signal-to-noise ratio]]\n* [[Timbre]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sengpielaudio.com/calculator-thd.htm Conversion: Distortion attenuation in dB to distortion factor THD in %]\n* [http://www.rohde-schwarz.com/appnote/1GA56 Swept Harmonic Distortion Measurements]\n* [http://www.rohde-schwarz.com/appnote/1GA55 Harmonic Distortion Measurements in the Presence of Noise]\n\n[[Category:Electrical parameters]]\n[[Category:Audio amplifier specifications]]\n", "name_user": "Skvery", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDefinitions and examples", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Total_harmonic_distortion"}
{"title_page": "Tom Malinowski", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Tom Malinowski\n|image        = Tom Malinowski, official portrait, 116th congress.jpg\n|state        = [[New Jersey]]\n|district     = {{ushr|NJ|7|7th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2019\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Leonard Lance]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]\n|president1   = [[Barack Obama]]\n|deputy1      = [[Virginia L. Bennett]]\n|term_start1  = April 3, 2014\n|term_end1    = January 20, 2017\n|predecessor1 = [[Michael Posner (lawyer)|Michael Posner]]\n|successor1   = [[Robert Destro]]\n|birth_date   = {{nowrap|{{birth date and age|1965|9|23}}}}\n|birth_place  = [[S\u0142upsk]], [[Poland]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education    = [[University of California, Berkeley]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[St Antony's College, Oxford]] ([[Master of Philosophy|MPhil]])\n|website      = {{url|malinowski.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Tom P. Malinowski''' (born September 23, 1965)<ref name=\"AllGov\"/> is an  [[United States|American]] politician and diplomat who is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]]. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he previously served as [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]] in the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]]. Malinowski was first elected in [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections|2018]], defeating [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] incumbent [[Leonard Lance]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski Declares|url=https://www.insidernj.com/press-release/tom-malinowski-declares-candidacy-7th-congressional-district/|publisher=InsiderNJ|date=October 2, 2017|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New Jersey Primary Election Results |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/06/05/us/elections/results-new-jersey-primary-elections.html |accessdate=8 August 2018 |publisher=New York Times |date=June 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMalinowski was born in [[S\u0142upsk]], Poland, and lived in [[Brwin\u00f3w]] until he left the country at the age of six with his mother, Joanna, who married [[Blair Clark]]. He was raised in [[Princeton, New Jersey]], and graduated from [[Princeton High School (New Jersey)|Princeton High School]] in 1983, where he wrote for the school newspaper ''The Tower'' and was an intern in the office of Senator [[Bill Bradley]].<ref name=\"AllGov\">{{cite web|title=Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor: Who Is Tom Malinowski?|url=http://www.allgov.com/news/appointments-and-resignations/assistant-secretary-of-state-for-democracy-human-rights-and-labor-who-is-tom-malinowski-130721?news=850617|publisher=AllGov|date=July 21, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[political science]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]], in 1987 and a [[Master of Philosophy]] from [[St Antony's College, Oxford]], in 1991, where he was a [[Rhodes Scholar]].<ref name=\"AllGov\"/><ref name=\"State\">{{cite web|title=Tom Malinowski|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/224368.htm|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=April 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nMalinowski began his government career as a special assistant for Senator [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]] in 1988. After attending Oxford, Malinowski worked for the [[Institute for Human Sciences]] in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]], and later as a research assistant for the [[Ford Foundation]] in 1993.<ref name=\"State\"/> From 1994 to 1998, Malinowski was a speechwriter for secretaries of state [[Warren Christopher]] and [[Madeleine Albright]], as well as a member of the [[Policy Planning Staff (United States)|Policy Planning Staff]] at the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]].<ref name=\"OpenSecrets\"/> From 1998 to 2001, Malinowski served as senior director on the [[United States National Security Council|National Security Council]] at the [[White House]], where he oversaw the drafting of President [[Bill Clinton]]'s foreign policy speeches and [[strategic communications]] efforts around the world.<ref name=\"State\"/><ref name=\"OpenSecrets\"/>\n\n==Human Rights Watch==\nFrom 2001 to 2013, Malinowski was a lobbyist for [[Human Rights Watch]].<ref name=\"State\"/><ref name=\"OpenSecrets\">{{cite web|title=Malinowski, Tom|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/revolving/rev_summary.php?id=78011|publisher=[[Center for Responsive Politics]]|date=April 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=twsPolitico0099/> In this position, he advocated for terrorists' rights during the [[War on Terror]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scher |first1=Brent |title=NJ Dem Tom Malinowski Tries and Fails to Defend Record of \u2018Lobbying for Terrorist Rights\u2019|url=https://freebeacon.com/politics/nj-dem-tom-malinowski-tries-fails-to-defend-record-of-lobbying-for-terrorist-rights/|publisher=[[The Washington Free Beacon]]|date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> Going as far as to say that [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay]] should be shut down.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Malinowski |first1=Tom |title=Four Good Reasons Why Guantanamo Should Be Closed|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2006/11/22/four-good-reasons-why-guantanamo-should-be-closed# |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=November 22, 2006}}</ref> Malinowski also campaigned against American support of the Israeli military. Malinowski opposed the United States supplying the Israeli Defense Forces with cluster munitions and asked then-Senator [[Hillary Clinton]] to not support Israel\u2019s construction of an \u2018illegal\u2019 wall in the West Bank.<ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |title=Human Rights Watch Lobbying Activity|url=https://freebeacon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Screen-Shot-2018-07-20-at-3.00.16-PM.png |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Malinowski |first1=Tom |title=Human Rights watch Lobbying Activity|url=https://freebeacon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Screen-Shot-2018-07-20-at-3.04.26-PM.png |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\n== Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor ==\nMalinowski was seen by some<ref name=\"Wapo3\">{{cite web|title=Nonprofit Groups Seeking Exceptions to Lobby Rule|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/21/us/politics/21lobby.html|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=April 20, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Wapo4\">{{cite web|title=The Good Lobbyist|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/23/opinion/23thu3.html?mcubz=2|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=April 22, 2006}}</ref> as a likely nominee for [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]] but his previous registration as a lobbyist while at Human Rights Watch necessitated a waiver from the President. On July 8, 2013, during President Obama's second term, Malinowski was nominated to serve as [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]].<ref>{{cite web|title=President Obama Announces More Key Administration Posts|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/07/08/president-obama-announces-more-key-administration-posts|publisher=[[White House]]|date=July 8, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=White House hires lobbyist Malinowski|last=Heil|first=Emily|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/in-the-loop/post/white-house-taps-tom-malinowski-for-human-rights-post/2013/07/09/1395416e-e8a3-11e2-a301-ea5a8116d211_blog.html|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=July 9, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski testified before the [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]] on September 24, 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement for the Record by Tom Malinowski, Nominee for Assistant Secretary of State|url=http://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Malinowski.pdf|publisher=[[United States Senate]]|date=September 24, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> and was confirmed by the [[U.S. Senate]] on April 2, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Senate confirms State Dept. nominee|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/04/09/senate-confirms-state-dept-nominee/|work=[[Washington Blade]]|date=April 9, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Senate Confirms Tom Malinowski as New Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor|url=http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/press-release/senate-confirms-tom-malinowski-new-assistant-secretary-state-democracy-human-rights|publisher=[[Human Rights First]]|date=April 2, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski confirmed at DRL|url=http://www.demdigest.net/malinowski-confirmed-drl/|publisher=Democracy Digest|date=April 4, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> According to columnist [[Jennifer Rubin (journalist)|Jennifer Rubin]], Malinowski was praised in 2014 by leaders from both parties for his defense of human rights and his work toward ending torture.<ref name=twsWashPost040>Washington Post, Jennifer Rubin, February 21, 2014, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/right-turn/wp/2014/02/21/free-tom-malinowksi/ Free Tom Malinowski], Retrieved May 23, 2018, \"...Tom is widely respected for the indispensable role he has played in defense of human rights and fundamental freedoms, from ending torture to advancing democracy ... He received wide support from Democrats and Republicans who have been united in their criticism of the administration\u2019s ... attitude toward human rights....</ref>\n\nWhile working in the State Department, Malinowski spearheaded efforts to assist persecuted religious minorities targeted by [[ISIS]] in [[Iraq]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A/S Malinowski Briefs Congressional Leaders on ISIL\u2019s Persecution of Religious Minorities in Iraq and Syria=|url=https://geneva.usmission.gov/2014/09/12/as-malinowski-briefs-congressional-leaders-on-isils-persecution-of-religious-minorities-in-iraq-and-syria/|publisher=United States of America Geneva Mission|date=September 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski Testimony|url=https://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Malinowski_Testimony.pdf|publisher=[[U.S. Senate]]|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> He also oversaw efforts to sanction [[North Korea]]n officials for human rights abuses and increase the flow of uncensored information into the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. compiling list of North Korea human rights violators|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2016/04/27/US-compiling-list-of-North-Korea-human-rights-violators/8071461768502/|publisher=[[UPI]]|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanctions on N.K. leader 'just the start,' more blacklisting to come: senior U.S. diplomat|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2016/07/08/0401000000AEN20160708001200315.html| publisher=[[Yonhap]]|date=July 8, 2016}}</ref> He led State Department efforts to defend the [[LGBT]] community around the world and oversaw the appointment of the first [[Randy W. Berry|Special Envoy for LGBT rights]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Support for Gay Rights in Africa|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/29/opinion/support-for-gay-rights-in-africa.html?mcubz=1&mtrref=undefined&assetType=opinion|publisher=|date=December 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Special Envoy for LGBT Rights|url=http://www.hrc.org/blog/welcome-to-the-special-envoy-for-lgbt-rights|publisher=[[Human Rights Campaign]]|date=February 27, 2015}}</ref> Malinowski backed [[United Nations]]' efforts to investigate possible [[Alleged war crimes during the final stages of the Sri Lankan Civil War|war crimes]] committed during the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. to Support Sri Lanka Plan to Investigate War Crimes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/27/world/asia/united-states-supports-sri-lanka-investigation-of-war-crimes.html?mtrref=undefined|publisher=[[NY Times]]|date=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He also worked on decreasing civilian casualties from US military operations in the [[Middle East]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Obama\u2019s New Executive Order Increases Drone Transparency, Official Says|url=https://www.washingtonreport.me/2016-august/september/obamas-new-executive-order-increases-drone-transparency-official-says.html|publisher=[[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]]|date=August 2016}}</ref> and assisted with sanctioning Russian officials for [[Magnitsky Act|human rights abuses]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Five Russians blacklisted for alleged human rights abuses|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/five-russians-blacklisted-for-human-rights-abuses/2017/01/09/1b00068c-d6b6-11e6-9f9f-5cdb4b7f8dd7_story.html|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=January 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Malinowski and Omar in 2019.png|thumb|Malinowski with [[Ilhan Omar]] in [[Washington DC]], 2019]]\nIn July 2014, Malinowski was [[persona non grata|expelled]] by [[Bahrain]]'s [[Government of Bahrain|government]] after meeting with members of an opposition group in the course of a scheduled visit.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|title=US diplomat Tom Malinowski expelled from Bahrain|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-28204511|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bahrain: U.S. diplomat 'unwelcome and should immediately leave'|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/07/08/world/meast/bahrain-us-diplomat-unwelcome/|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=July 8, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bahrain expels top US diplomat after meeting with main opposition group|url=https://www.rt.com/news/171084-bahrain-expels-us-diplomat/|publisher=[[RT (TV network)|RT]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> The foreign ministry of Bahrain argued that Malinowski's meeting improperly intervened in the country's affairs but noted the incident would not affect [[Bahrain\u2013United States relations]].<ref name=\"BBC\"/> The [[U.S. State Department]] released a statement of concern about the actions while [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]] called Bahrain's actions unacceptable and contrary to diplomatic protocol.<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite web|last=Schwartz|first=Felicia|title=Tension Between Bahrain and U.S. Continues Over Diplomat's Expulsion|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tension-between-bahrain-and-u-s-continues-over-diplomats-expulsion-1405387624|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=July 14, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Statement on the Decision by the Government of Bahrain To Find Assistant Secretary Malinowski Persona Non Grata and To Expel Him From Bahrain|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2014/07/228839.htm|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski returned to the country in December 2014 with the [[Anne W. Patterson|assistant secretary of state for Near Eastern affairs]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gordon|first=Michael|title=Expelled U.S. Official to Return to Bahrain|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/03/world/middleeast/bahrain-us-human-rights-official-tom-malinowski.html?_r=0|work=[[New York Times]]|date=December 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Press Availability with A/S Tom Malinowski and A/S Anne Patterson|url=http://bahrain.usembassy.gov/pas-120414.html|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=December 4, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414204305/http://bahrain.usembassy.gov/pas-120414.html|archivedate=April 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the end of his tenure at the State Department, Malinowski joined fellow former Obama officials to lobby Congress in an effort to prevent the [[Trump Administration]] from lifting the [[International sanctions during the Ukrainian crisis|sanctions]] on [[Russia]] following its [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|invasion of Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Diplomats: Trump Team Sought to Lift Sanctions on Russia|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/former-diplomats-trump-team-sought-lift-sanctions-russia-n767406|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=June 1, 2017}}</ref> He criticized [[Donald Trump]] for having an \"obscene fondness\" for the world's tyrants and for instituting a \"complete departure from decades of American tradition.\"<ref name=twsPolitico0099>Politico magazine, Susan B. Glasser, June 19, 2017, [https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/06/19/tom-malinowski-man-who-argued-with-dictators-215278 The Man Who Argued With Dictators: Tom Malinowski spent years trying to get President Obama to care more about human rights. Now, he\u2019s figuring out what to do with a president who doesn\u2019t seem to care at all.], Retrieved May 24, 2018, \"...Malinowski spent the past few years pushing Obama from the inside on human rights ... former Washington director of Human Rights Watch ... leading the resistance from the outside to Trump and what he calls his \u201cobscene\u201d fondness for the world\u2019s tyrants....\"</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\nOn October 2, 2017, Malinowski announced his candidacy for U.S. Congress in [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]] in the [[2018 United States elections|2018 midterm elections]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kamisar|first1=Ben|title=Obama State Department official to run for House in NJ|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/353408-obama-state-department-official-to-run-for-house-in-nj|accessdate=16 May 2018|publisher=The Hill|date=October 2, 2017}}</ref> He decided to run for Congress after the [[2016 United States presidential election|November 2016 election of Donald Trump]], which he saw as an indication that America was in \"deep trouble.\"<ref name=twsBloomberg445>Albert R. Hunt, May 2, 2018, Bloomberg News, [https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-05-02/democratic-house-candidates-look-mighty-familiar Some Democratic Candidates Look Mighty Familiar], Retrieved May 15, 2018, \"... Malinowski, an assistant secretary of State for President Obama and a State Department official under Clinton ... America, he believes, \"is in deep trouble.\"...\"</ref> Malinowski said he decided to run for office because of what he called the Trump administration's \"effort to take down the Affordable Care Act with no viable replacement. It was the Muslim ban, and attacks on immigrants, it was the tearing up of alliances and commitments internationally. It was the taking down of environmental protections, it was refusing to invest in infrastructure.\"<ref name=\"twsNBCWash11\">May 27, 2018, NBC News Washington (Channel 4), [https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/politics/Former-Obama-Staffers-Elections-483805841.html Fired Up by Trump, Dozens of Former Obama Staffers Run for Office: The surge of Democratic candidates with ties to Obama has the potential to fill state and federal legislatures with like-minded allies], Retrieved May 30, 2018, \"...it was the effort to take down the Affordable Care Act with no viable replacement...\"</ref>\n\nMalinowski supports the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] and criticized the Republican Party for \"whittling away at the Affordable Care Act year after year.\"<ref name=twsInsiderNJ44>Insider New Jersey, May 12, 2018, Staff writer, [https://www.insidernj.com/cd7-democratic-challenger-malinowski-formally-opens-main-headquarters-pallone/ CD7 Democratic Challenger Malinowski Formally Opens his Main Headquarters with Pallone], Retrieved May 14, 2018, \"... He\u2019ll fight to protect the Affordable Care Act.....\"</ref>  He supports raising the minimum wage to $15 per hour as well as enhanced collective bargaining rights and protections for workers.<ref name=twsNJGlobe11/>  Malinowski sees the Democratic Party, in contrast to the GOP, as promoting fiscal responsibility, law enforcement, family values, and patriotism.<ref name=\"twsWashPost0786\">E. J. Dionne, July 15, 2018, Washington Post, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/does-the-blue-wave-start-in-jersey/2018/07/15/db44a0b2-86e4-11e8-8f6c-46cb43e3f306_story.html?wpisrc=nl_headlines&wpmm=1 Does the blue wave start in Jersey?], Retrieved July 16, 2018</ref>\n\n[[File:Candidate for Congress NJ-7th Tom Malinowski at campaign headquarters speaking with a voter.jpg|thumb|upright|Malinowski at his campaign headquarters in [[Martinsville, New Jersey]]]]\nHis endorsements included the Hunterdon County Democratic Committee<ref name=\"twsNJHills41\">April 27, 2018, New Jersey Hills, [http://www.newjerseyhills.com/hunterdon_review/news/first-lady-tammy-murphy-to-speak-at-county-democratic-brunch/article_a25ed6e9-39ca-56e0-a286-f38ca8e86f59.html First Lady Tammy Murphy to speak at county Democratic brunch on Sunday, April 29], Retrieved May 15, 2018, \"...Tom Malinowski ... endorsed by the HCDC ...\"</ref> and the [[Communications Workers of America]].<ref name=\"twsNJGlobe11\">David Wildstein, April 23, 2018, New Jersey Globe, [https://newjerseyglobe.com/congress/cwa-endorses-malinowski/ CWA Endorses Malinowski], Retrieved May 15, 2018</ref> On June 5, 2018, he faced social worker Peter Jacob and lawyer Goutam Jois.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Jersey's 7th Congressional District election, 2018|url=https://ballotpedia.org/New_Jersey%27s_7th_Congressional_District_election,_2018|accessdate=8 May 2018|publisher=Ballotpedia}}</ref> He defeated Jacob and Jois, receiving 66.8% of the vote and winning all counties in the district<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-jersey-house-district-7-primary-election|title=New Jersey Primary Election Results: Seventh House District|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njelections.org/assets/pdf/election-results/2018/2018-official-primary-results-us-house.pdf|title=Candidates for House of Representatives For PRIMARY ELECTION 06/05/2018 Election,|last=|first=|date=July 20, 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Malinowski went onto to defeat incumbent Republican [[Leonard Lance]].\n\nMalinowski criticized Lance, saying he \"shifted to the right when he was scared of the [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] and he's moving to the left when he's scared of his increasingly moderate and energized constituents.\"<ref name=\"twsNJcom441\">Jonathan D. Salant, May 14, 2018, NJ.com, [http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/05/how_njs_most_endangered_congressman_is_trying_to_w.html This N.J. Republican is in big trouble because of Trump. Here's what he's doing about it.], Retrieved May 15, 2018</ref> On November 6, Malinowski won the election, receiving 51.7% of the vote. While Malinowski and Lance each carried three of the six counties in the district, Malinowski won the district's shares of Somerset and Union counties by a combined 22,300 votes, more than the overall margin of 16,200 votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-jersey-house-district-7|title=New Jersey\u2019s Seventh House District Election Results: Tom Malinowski vs. Leonard Lance|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njelections.org/assets/pdf/election-results/2018/2018-official-general-election-results-us-house.pdf|title=Official List Candidates for House of Representatives For GENERAL ELECTION 11/06/2018 Election|last=|first=|date=December 3, 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref> When he took office in January 2019, he became the first Democrat to represent the 7th and its predecessors since 1961.\n\nOn February 26, 2020, Malinowski stated that he would \u201cabsolutely\u201d support [[Bernie Sanders]] if he were the Democratic Presidential nominee.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mascaro |first1=Lisa |title=Pelosi urges Democratic unity amid Sanders\u2019 campaign surge |url=https://apnews.com/7ef003d3d777ba44bb4e24fed66809f8 |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=The Associated Press |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n\n* [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|'''Committee on Foreign Affairs''']]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism|Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|'''Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure''']]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials|Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n\n=== Caucus memberships ===\n* '''[[LGBT Equality Caucus]]'''\n* '''[[New Democrat Coalition]]'''\n* '''End Corruption Caucus'''<ref name=\"Malinowski Press Release 2020.01.21\">{{cite web |title=Representative Malinowski Leads Fight To End Corruption in Washington |url=https://malinowski.house.gov/media/press-releases/representative-malinowski-leads-fight-end-corruption-washington |website=Tom Malinowski Congressional Web Site |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Congressman Max Rose Press Release 2020.01.16\">{{cite web |title=10 Years After Disastrous Citizens United Decision, Rose, Porter, Freshmen Dems Launch New \u2018End Corruption\u2019 Caucus |url=https://maxrose.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=2450 |website=Max Rose Congressional Web Site |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===COVID-19===\nMalinowski joked during an April 2020 livestream with constituents that he would withhold shipments of [[Lysol]] disinfectant to the state of [[Kentucky]] until [[Senate Majority Leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]], relents in his opposition to Democrat-backed vote-by-mail measures amid the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]]. He was referring to a [[Reckitt Benckiser]] manufacturing plant located in [[Hillsborough Township, New Jersey|Hillsborough Township]] which produces 100% of the United States' supply of Lysol disinfectant.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Snowflack |first1=Fred |title=Kentucky Strikes Back at Malinowski |url=https://www.insidernj.com/kentucky-strikes-back-at-malinowski/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=Insider NJ |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Saxena |first1=Vivek |title=\u2018We make 100 percent\u2019: NJ Dem \u2018jokes\u2019 about withholding Lysol products to strongarm Mitch McConnell |url=https://www.bizpacreview.com/2020/04/10/we-make-100-percent-nj-dem-jokes-about-withholding-lysol-products-to-strongarm-mitch-mcconnell-906928 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=Biz Pac Review |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n\"There\u2019s nothing funny about a member of Congress threatening to withhold vital supplies from Kentuckians during a deadly outbreak,\u201d [[Republican Party of Kentucky]] spokesman Mike Lonergan said in response to the comments. \u201cAt a time when families and communities across the country are suffering, people are coming together to fight the coronavirus. This Democrat congressman\u2019s threats need and deserve to be condemned.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Creitz |first1=Charles |title=Democratic rep jokes about withholding Lysol shipments to Kentucky in swipe at McConnell |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/malinowski-jokes-withholding-lysol-shipments-kentucky-mcconnell |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=Fox News |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski added that this was a 'fantasy' of his that is unlikely actually work.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kane |first1=Paul |title=For House incumbents, campaigning during a pandemic means providing help |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/for-house-incumbents-campaigning-in-the-time-of-a-pandemic-means-providing-help/2020/04/11/baa8695e-7c12-11ea-b6ff-597f170df8f8_story.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=The Washington Post |date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Illegal Immigrants===\nAt an August 2019 town hall, Malinowski told constituents that illegal immigrants are needed to mow \"our beautiful lawns\" and perform menial jobs rejected by tech-focused teenagers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ferrechio |first1=Susan |title=Democratic lawmaker: Illegal immigrants needed to mow 'our beautiful lawns' |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/congress/democratic-lawmaker-illegal-immigrants-needed-to-mow-our-beautiful-lawns |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Washington Examiner |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wulfsohn |first1=Joseph |title=Dem Rep. Tom Malinowski: We need illegal immigrants to 'mow our beautiful lawns' |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/dem-rep-tom-malinowski-illegal-immigrants-to-mow-lawns |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Fox News |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref> The comments made national headlines and drew backlash from critics who called Malinowski \"out of touch\". Questions were raised as to whether Malinowski pays illegal immigrants to mow his personal lawn.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moritz-Rabson |first1=Daniel |title=DEMOCRATIC CONGRESSMAN SAYS UNDOCUMENTED IMMIGRANTS ARE GOOD FOR 'MOWING OUR BEAUTIFUL LAWNS' |url=https://www.newsweek.com/democratic-congressman-says-undocumented-immigrants-are-good-mowing-our-beautiful-lawns-1455893 |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Newsweek |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Prince |first1=Molly |title=WATCH: Dem Lawmaker Says Illegal Immigrants Are Needed To Mow \u2018Our Beautiful Lawns\u2019 |url=https://www.dailywire.com/news/watch-dem-lawmaker-says-illegal-immigrants-are-molly-prince |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=The Daily Wire |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Meads |first1=Timothy |title=WATCH: Dem Lawmaker Says Illegal Immigrants Are Needed To Mow \u2018Our Beautiful Lawns\u2019 |url=New Jersey Democrat: We Need Illegals To Mow Our 'Beautiful Lawns'e |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Townhall |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Impeachment===\nMalinowski was the first member of the New Jersey congressional delegation to call to begin the impeachment inquiry of President [[Donald Trump]] in May 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moran |first1=Tom |title=Malinowski, the first Jersey House member to favor impeachment hearings, explains why|url=https://www.nj.com/opinion/2019/05/malinowski-the-first-jersey-house-member-to-favor-impeachment-hearings-explains-why-moran.html |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=NJ.com |date=May 29, 2019}}</ref> At the time, he was the only swing-district Democrat to support opening an impeachment inquiry into the President. Malinowski came under sharp criticism from constituents at subsequent town hall meetings as well as in press.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff |first1=The |title=Malinowski discovers vocal impeachment opposition at Branchburg town hall |url=https://savejersey.com/2019/12/malinowski-discovers-vocal-impeachment-opposition-at-branchburg-town-hall/ |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Save Jersey |date=December 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Parker-Maygar |first1=Alex |title=Malinowski talks impeachment at town hall as House vote looms |url=https://www.newjerseyhills.com/videos-malinowski-talks-impeachment-at-town-hall-as-house-vote/article_c3f3ed11-b7ff-5300-b051-24899abb62f2.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=New Jersey Globe |date=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMalinowski owns a home in [[Washington, D.C.]], and was registered to vote there as of March 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pizarro |first1=Max |title=Residency Question Hounds Malinowski on Eve of Union County Vote |url=https://www.insidernj.com/residency-question-hounds-malinowski-eve-union-county-vote/ |accessdate=16 July 2018 |publisher=InsiderNJ |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref> He began renting a home in [[Rocky Hill, New Jersey]], in September 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brodesser-Akner |first1=Claude |title=What's really going on with all these 'carpetbagger' political attacks in New Jersey? |url=https://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/07/hed_whats_really_going_on_with_all_these_carpetbag.html |accessdate=17 July 2018 |publisher=NJ.com |date=July 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pathe |first1=Simone |title=Could Past DC Residency Be Liability for Some Democrats? |url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/past-dc-residency-liability-democrats |accessdate=16 July 2018 |publisher=Roll Call |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski's stepfather [[Blair Clark]] was a journalist. Clark's sister was [[Anne Clark Martindell|Anne Martindell]], a member of the [[New Jersey State Senate]] (1974\u20131977) and a [[List of ambassadors of the United States to New Zealand|United States ambassador to New Zealand]] (1979\u20131981).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wildstein |first1=David |title=Malinowski and the residency thing |url=https://newjerseyglobe.com/section-2/malinowski-residency-thing/ |accessdate= August 8, 2018 |publisher=New Jersey Globe |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski has one daughter, Emily.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Muscavage |first1=Nick |title= NJ elections: Democrat Tom Malinowski unseats Republican Leonard Lance in NJ's 7th Congressional District  |url=https://www.mycentraljersey.com/story/news/politics/2018/11/07/nj-7th-district-congress-tom-malinowski-defeats-leonard-lance/1902521002/ |accessdate= March 3, 2020 |publisher= Courier News and Home News Tribune |date=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://malinowski.house.gov/ Congressman Tom Malinowski] official U.S. House website\n*[https://malinowskifornj.com/ Tom Malinowski for Congress]\n{{CongLinks|fec=H8NJ07223|votesmart=179645|congbio=M001203|congress=tom-malinowski/M001203}}\n\n{{Commons category|Tomasz P. Malinowski}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Posner (lawyer)|Michael Posner]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Virginia L. Bennett]]<br>{{small|Acting}}}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Leonard Lance]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from New Jersey|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Elaine Luria]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=383rd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ben McAdams]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Members of the U.S. House of Representatives}}\n{{NJ-FedRep}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malinowski, Tom}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Antony's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Human Rights Watch people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:New Jersey Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Princeton, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Rocky Hill, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from S\u0142upsk]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Princeton High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Assistant Secretaries of State]]\n[[Category:United States National Security Council staffers]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Progressivism in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Tom Malinowski\n|image        = Tom Malinowski, official portrait, 116th congress.jpg\n|state        = [[New Jersey]]\n|district     = {{ushr|NJ|7|7th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2019\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Leonard Lance]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]\n|president1   = [[Barack Obama]]\n|deputy1      = [[Virginia L. Bennett]]\n|term_start1  = April 3, 2014\n|term_end1    = January 20, 2017\n|predecessor1 = [[Michael Posner (lawyer)|Michael Posner]]\n|successor1   = [[Robert Destro]]\n|birth_date   = {{nowrap|{{birth date and age|1965|9|23}}}}\n|birth_place  = [[S\u0142upsk]], [[Poland]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education    = [[University of California, Berkeley]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[St Antony's College, Oxford]] ([[Master of Philosophy|MPhil]])\n|website      = {{url|malinowski.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Tom P. Malinowski''' (born September 23, 1965)<ref name=\"AllGov\"/> is an  [[United States|American]] politician and diplomat who is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]]. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he previously served as [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]] in the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]]. Malinowski was first elected in [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections|2018]], defeating [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] incumbent [[Leonard Lance]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski Declares|url=https://www.insidernj.com/press-release/tom-malinowski-declares-candidacy-7th-congressional-district/|publisher=InsiderNJ|date=October 2, 2017|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New Jersey Primary Election Results |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/06/05/us/elections/results-new-jersey-primary-elections.html |accessdate=8 August 2018 |publisher=New York Times |date=June 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMalinowski was born in [[S\u0142upsk]], Poland, and lived in [[Brwin\u00f3w]] until he left the country at the age of six with his mother, Joanna, who married [[Blair Clark]]. He was raised in [[Princeton, New Jersey]], and graduated from [[Princeton High School (New Jersey)|Princeton High School]] in 1983, where he wrote for the school newspaper ''The Tower'' and was an intern in the office of Senator [[Bill Bradley]].<ref name=\"AllGov\">{{cite web|title=Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor: Who Is Tom Malinowski?|url=http://www.allgov.com/news/appointments-and-resignations/assistant-secretary-of-state-for-democracy-human-rights-and-labor-who-is-tom-malinowski-130721?news=850617|publisher=AllGov|date=July 21, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[political science]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]], in 1987 and a [[Master of Philosophy]] from [[St Antony's College, Oxford]], in 1991, where he was a [[Rhodes Scholar]].<ref name=\"AllGov\"/><ref name=\"State\">{{cite web|title=Tom Malinowski|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/224368.htm|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=April 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nMalinowski began his government career as a special assistant for Senator [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]] in 1988. After attending Oxford, Malinowski worked for the [[Institute for Human Sciences]] in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]], and later as a research assistant for the [[Ford Foundation]] in 1993.<ref name=\"State\"/> From 1994 to 1998, Malinowski was a speechwriter for secretaries of state [[Warren Christopher]] and [[Madeleine Albright]], as well as a member of the [[Policy Planning Staff (United States)|Policy Planning Staff]] at the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]].<ref name=\"OpenSecrets\"/> From 1998 to 2001, Malinowski served as senior director on the [[United States National Security Council|National Security Council]] at the [[White House]], where he oversaw the drafting of President [[Bill Clinton]]'s foreign policy speeches and [[strategic communications]] efforts around the world.<ref name=\"State\"/><ref name=\"OpenSecrets\"/>\n\n==Human Rights Watch==\nFrom 2001 to 2013, Malinowski was a lobbyist for [[Human Rights Watch]].<ref name=\"State\"/><ref name=\"OpenSecrets\">{{cite web|title=Malinowski, Tom|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/revolving/rev_summary.php?id=78011|publisher=[[Center for Responsive Politics]]|date=April 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=twsPolitico0099/> In this position, he advocated for terrorists' rights during the [[War on Terror]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scher |first1=Brent |title=NJ Dem Tom Malinowski Tries and Fails to Defend Record of \u2018Lobbying for Terrorist Rights\u2019|url=https://freebeacon.com/politics/nj-dem-tom-malinowski-tries-fails-to-defend-record-of-lobbying-for-terrorist-rights/|publisher=[[The Washington Free Beacon]]|date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> Going as far as to say that [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay]] should be shut down.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Malinowski |first1=Tom |title=Four Good Reasons Why Guantanamo Should Be Closed|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2006/11/22/four-good-reasons-why-guantanamo-should-be-closed# |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=November 22, 2006}}</ref> Malinowski also campaigned against American support of the Israeli military. Malinowski opposed the United States supplying the Israeli Defense Forces with cluster munitions and asked then-Senator [[Hillary Clinton]] to not support Israel\u2019s construction of an \u2018illegal\u2019 wall in the West Bank.<ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |title=Human Rights Watch Lobbying Activity|url=https://freebeacon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Screen-Shot-2018-07-20-at-3.00.16-PM.png |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Malinowski |first1=Tom |title=Human Rights watch Lobbying Activity|url=https://freebeacon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Screen-Shot-2018-07-20-at-3.04.26-PM.png |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\n== Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor ==\nMalinowski was seen by some<ref name=\"Wapo3\">{{cite web|title=Nonprofit Groups Seeking Exceptions to Lobby Rule|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/21/us/politics/21lobby.html|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=April 20, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Wapo4\">{{cite web|title=The Good Lobbyist|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/23/opinion/23thu3.html?mcubz=2|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=April 22, 2006}}</ref> as a likely nominee for [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]] but his previous registration as a lobbyist while at Human Rights Watch necessitated a waiver from the President. On July 8, 2013, during President Obama's second term, Malinowski was nominated to serve as [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]].<ref>{{cite web|title=President Obama Announces More Key Administration Posts|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/07/08/president-obama-announces-more-key-administration-posts|publisher=[[White House]]|date=July 8, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=White House hires lobbyist Malinowski|last=Heil|first=Emily|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/in-the-loop/post/white-house-taps-tom-malinowski-for-human-rights-post/2013/07/09/1395416e-e8a3-11e2-a301-ea5a8116d211_blog.html|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=July 9, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski testified before the [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]] on September 24, 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement for the Record by Tom Malinowski, Nominee for Assistant Secretary of State|url=http://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Malinowski.pdf|publisher=[[United States Senate]]|date=September 24, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> and was confirmed by the [[U.S. Senate]] on April 2, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Senate confirms State Dept. nominee|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/04/09/senate-confirms-state-dept-nominee/|work=[[Washington Blade]]|date=April 9, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Senate Confirms Tom Malinowski as New Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor|url=http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/press-release/senate-confirms-tom-malinowski-new-assistant-secretary-state-democracy-human-rights|publisher=[[Human Rights First]]|date=April 2, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski confirmed at DRL|url=http://www.demdigest.net/malinowski-confirmed-drl/|publisher=Democracy Digest|date=April 4, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> According to columnist [[Jennifer Rubin (journalist)|Jennifer Rubin]], Malinowski was praised in 2014 by leaders from both parties for his defense of human rights and his work toward ending torture.<ref name=twsWashPost040>Washington Post, Jennifer Rubin, February 21, 2014, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/right-turn/wp/2014/02/21/free-tom-malinowksi/ Free Tom Malinowski], Retrieved May 23, 2018, \"...Tom is widely respected for the indispensable role he has played in defense of human rights and fundamental freedoms, from ending torture to advancing democracy ... He received wide support from Democrats and Republicans who have been united in their criticism of the administration\u2019s ... attitude toward human rights....</ref>\n\nWhile working in the State Department, Malinowski spearheaded efforts to assist persecuted religious minorities targeted by [[ISIS]] in [[Iraq]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A/S Malinowski Briefs Congressional Leaders on ISIL\u2019s Persecution of Religious Minorities in Iraq and Syria=|url=https://geneva.usmission.gov/2014/09/12/as-malinowski-briefs-congressional-leaders-on-isils-persecution-of-religious-minorities-in-iraq-and-syria/|publisher=United States of America Geneva Mission|date=September 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski Testimony|url=https://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Malinowski_Testimony.pdf|publisher=[[U.S. Senate]]|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> He also oversaw efforts to sanction [[North Korea]]n officials for human rights abuses and increase the flow of uncensored information into the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. compiling list of North Korea human rights violators|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2016/04/27/US-compiling-list-of-North-Korea-human-rights-violators/8071461768502/|publisher=[[UPI]]|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanctions on N.K. leader 'just the start,' more blacklisting to come: senior U.S. diplomat|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2016/07/08/0401000000AEN20160708001200315.html| publisher=[[Yonhap]]|date=July 8, 2016}}</ref> He led State Department efforts to defend the [[LGBT]] community around the world and oversaw the appointment of the first [[Randy W. Berry|Special Envoy for LGBT rights]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Support for Gay Rights in Africa|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/29/opinion/support-for-gay-rights-in-africa.html?mcubz=1&mtrref=undefined&assetType=opinion|publisher=|date=December 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Special Envoy for LGBT Rights|url=http://www.hrc.org/blog/welcome-to-the-special-envoy-for-lgbt-rights|publisher=[[Human Rights Campaign]]|date=February 27, 2015}}</ref> Malinowski backed [[United Nations]]' efforts to investigate possible [[Alleged war crimes during the final stages of the Sri Lankan Civil War|war crimes]] committed during the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. to Support Sri Lanka Plan to Investigate War Crimes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/27/world/asia/united-states-supports-sri-lanka-investigation-of-war-crimes.html?mtrref=undefined|publisher=[[NY Times]]|date=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He also worked on decreasing civilian casualties from US military operations in the [[Middle East]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Obama\u2019s New Executive Order Increases Drone Transparency, Official Says|url=https://www.washingtonreport.me/2016-august/september/obamas-new-executive-order-increases-drone-transparency-official-says.html|publisher=[[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]]|date=August 2016}}</ref> and assisted with sanctioning Russian officials for [[Magnitsky Act|human rights abuses]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Five Russians blacklisted for alleged human rights abuses|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/five-russians-blacklisted-for-human-rights-abuses/2017/01/09/1b00068c-d6b6-11e6-9f9f-5cdb4b7f8dd7_story.html|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=January 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Malinowski and Omar in 2019.png|thumb|Malinowski with [[Ilhan Omar]] in [[Washington DC]], 2019]]\nIn July 2014, Malinowski was [[persona non grata|expelled]] by [[Bahrain]]'s [[Government of Bahrain|government]] after meeting with members of an opposition group in the course of a scheduled visit.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|title=US diplomat Tom Malinowski expelled from Bahrain|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-28204511|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bahrain: U.S. diplomat 'unwelcome and should immediately leave'|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/07/08/world/meast/bahrain-us-diplomat-unwelcome/|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=July 8, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bahrain expels top US diplomat after meeting with main opposition group|url=https://www.rt.com/news/171084-bahrain-expels-us-diplomat/|publisher=[[RT (TV network)|RT]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> The foreign ministry of Bahrain argued that Malinowski's meeting improperly intervened in the country's affairs but noted the incident would not affect [[Bahrain\u2013United States relations]].<ref name=\"BBC\"/> The [[U.S. State Department]] released a statement of concern about the actions while [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]] called Bahrain's actions unacceptable and contrary to diplomatic protocol.<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite web|last=Schwartz|first=Felicia|title=Tension Between Bahrain and U.S. Continues Over Diplomat's Expulsion|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tension-between-bahrain-and-u-s-continues-over-diplomats-expulsion-1405387624|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=July 14, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Statement on the Decision by the Government of Bahrain To Find Assistant Secretary Malinowski Persona Non Grata and To Expel Him From Bahrain|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2014/07/228839.htm|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski returned to the country in December 2014 with the [[Anne W. Patterson|assistant secretary of state for Near Eastern affairs]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gordon|first=Michael|title=Expelled U.S. Official to Return to Bahrain|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/03/world/middleeast/bahrain-us-human-rights-official-tom-malinowski.html?_r=0|work=[[New York Times]]|date=December 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Press Availability with A/S Tom Malinowski and A/S Anne Patterson|url=http://bahrain.usembassy.gov/pas-120414.html|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=December 4, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414204305/http://bahrain.usembassy.gov/pas-120414.html|archivedate=April 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the end of his tenure at the State Department, Malinowski joined fellow former Obama officials to lobby Congress in an effort to prevent the [[Trump Administration]] from lifting the [[International sanctions during the Ukrainian crisis|sanctions]] on [[Russia]] following its [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|invasion of Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Diplomats: Trump Team Sought to Lift Sanctions on Russia|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/former-diplomats-trump-team-sought-lift-sanctions-russia-n767406|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=June 1, 2017}}</ref> He criticized [[Donald Trump]] for having an \"obscene fondness\" for the world's tyrants and for instituting a \"complete departure from decades of American tradition.\"<ref name=twsPolitico0099>Politico magazine, Susan B. Glasser, June 19, 2017, [https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/06/19/tom-malinowski-man-who-argued-with-dictators-215278 The Man Who Argued With Dictators: Tom Malinowski spent years trying to get President Obama to care more about human rights. Now, he\u2019s figuring out what to do with a president who doesn\u2019t seem to care at all.], Retrieved May 24, 2018, \"...Malinowski spent the past few years pushing Obama from the inside on human rights ... former Washington director of Human Rights Watch ... leading the resistance from the outside to Trump and what he calls his \u201cobscene\u201d fondness for the world\u2019s tyrants....\"</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\nOn October 2, 2017, Malinowski announced his candidacy for U.S. Congress in [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]] in the [[2018 United States elections|2018 midterm elections]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kamisar|first1=Ben|title=Obama State Department official to run for House in NJ|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/353408-obama-state-department-official-to-run-for-house-in-nj|accessdate=16 May 2018|publisher=The Hill|date=October 2, 2017}}</ref> He decided to run for Congress after the [[2016 United States presidential election|November 2016 election of Donald Trump]], which he saw as an indication that America was in \"deep trouble.\"<ref name=twsBloomberg445>Albert R. Hunt, May 2, 2018, Bloomberg News, [https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-05-02/democratic-house-candidates-look-mighty-familiar Some Democratic Candidates Look Mighty Familiar], Retrieved May 15, 2018, \"... Malinowski, an assistant secretary of State for President Obama and a State Department official under Clinton ... America, he believes, \"is in deep trouble.\"...\"</ref> Malinowski said he decided to run for office because of what he called the Trump administration's \"effort to take down the Affordable Care Act with no viable replacement. It was the Muslim ban, and attacks on immigrants, it was the tearing up of alliances and commitments internationally. It was the taking down of environmental protections, it was refusing to invest in infrastructure.\"<ref name=\"twsNBCWash11\">May 27, 2018, NBC News Washington (Channel 4), [https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/politics/Former-Obama-Staffers-Elections-483805841.html Fired Up by Trump, Dozens of Former Obama Staffers Run for Office: The surge of Democratic candidates with ties to Obama has the potential to fill state and federal legislatures with like-minded allies], Retrieved May 30, 2018, \"...it was the effort to take down the Affordable Care Act with no viable replacement...\"</ref>\n\nMalinowski supports the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] and criticized the Republican Party for \"whittling away at the Affordable Care Act year after year.\"<ref name=twsInsiderNJ44>Insider New Jersey, May 12, 2018, Staff writer, [https://www.insidernj.com/cd7-democratic-challenger-malinowski-formally-opens-main-headquarters-pallone/ CD7 Democratic Challenger Malinowski Formally Opens his Main Headquarters with Pallone], Retrieved May 14, 2018, \"... He\u2019ll fight to protect the Affordable Care Act.....\"</ref>  He supports raising the minimum wage to $15 per hour as well as enhanced collective bargaining rights and protections for workers.<ref name=twsNJGlobe11/>  Malinowski sees the Democratic Party, in contrast to the GOP, as promoting fiscal responsibility, law enforcement, family values, and patriotism.<ref name=\"twsWashPost0786\">E. J. Dionne, July 15, 2018, Washington Post, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/does-the-blue-wave-start-in-jersey/2018/07/15/db44a0b2-86e4-11e8-8f6c-46cb43e3f306_story.html?wpisrc=nl_headlines&wpmm=1 Does the blue wave start in Jersey?], Retrieved July 16, 2018</ref>\n\n[[File:Candidate for Congress NJ-7th Tom Malinowski at campaign headquarters speaking with a voter.jpg|thumb|upright|Malinowski at his campaign headquarters in [[Martinsville, New Jersey]]]]\nHis endorsements included the Hunterdon County Democratic Committee<ref name=\"twsNJHills41\">April 27, 2018, New Jersey Hills, [http://www.newjerseyhills.com/hunterdon_review/news/first-lady-tammy-murphy-to-speak-at-county-democratic-brunch/article_a25ed6e9-39ca-56e0-a286-f38ca8e86f59.html First Lady Tammy Murphy to speak at county Democratic brunch on Sunday, April 29], Retrieved May 15, 2018, \"...Tom Malinowski ... endorsed by the HCDC ...\"</ref> and the [[Communications Workers of America]].<ref name=\"twsNJGlobe11\">David Wildstein, April 23, 2018, New Jersey Globe, [https://newjerseyglobe.com/congress/cwa-endorses-malinowski/ CWA Endorses Malinowski], Retrieved May 15, 2018</ref> On June 5, 2018, he faced social worker Peter Jacob and lawyer Goutam Jois.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Jersey's 7th Congressional District election, 2018|url=https://ballotpedia.org/New_Jersey%27s_7th_Congressional_District_election,_2018|accessdate=8 May 2018|publisher=Ballotpedia}}</ref> He defeated Jacob and Jois, receiving 66.8% of the vote and winning all counties in the district<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-jersey-house-district-7-primary-election|title=New Jersey Primary Election Results: Seventh House District|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njelections.org/assets/pdf/election-results/2018/2018-official-primary-results-us-house.pdf|title=Candidates for House of Representatives For PRIMARY ELECTION 06/05/2018 Election,|last=|first=|date=July 20, 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Malinowski went onto to defeat incumbent Republican [[Leonard Lance]].\n\nMalinowski criticized Lance, saying he \"shifted to the right when he was scared of the [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] and he's moving to the left when he's scared of his increasingly moderate and energized constituents.\"<ref name=\"twsNJcom441\">Jonathan D. Salant, May 14, 2018, NJ.com, [http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/05/how_njs_most_endangered_congressman_is_trying_to_w.html This N.J. Republican is in big trouble because of Trump. Here's what he's doing about it.], Retrieved May 15, 2018</ref> On November 6, Malinowski won the election, receiving 51.7% of the vote. While Malinowski and Lance each carried three of the six counties in the district, Malinowski won the district's shares of Somerset and Union counties by a combined 22,300 votes, more than the overall margin of 16,200 votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-jersey-house-district-7|title=New Jersey\u2019s Seventh House District Election Results: Tom Malinowski vs. Leonard Lance|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njelections.org/assets/pdf/election-results/2018/2018-official-general-election-results-us-house.pdf|title=Official List Candidates for House of Representatives For GENERAL ELECTION 11/06/2018 Election|last=|first=|date=December 3, 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref> When he took office in January 2019, he became the first Democrat to represent the 7th and its predecessors since 1961.\n\nOn February 26, 2020, Malinowski stated that he would \u201cabsolutely\u201d support [[Bernie Sanders]] if he were the Democratic Presidential nominee.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mascaro |first1=Lisa |title=Pelosi urges Democratic unity amid Sanders\u2019 campaign surge |url=https://apnews.com/7ef003d3d777ba44bb4e24fed66809f8 |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=The Associated Press |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n\n* [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|'''Committee on Foreign Affairs''']]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism|Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|'''Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure''']]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials|Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n\n=== Caucus memberships ===\n* '''[[LGBT Equality Caucus]]'''\n* '''[[New Democrat Coalition]]'''\n* '''End Corruption Caucus'''<ref name=\"Malinowski Press Release 2020.01.21\">{{cite web |title=Representative Malinowski Leads Fight To End Corruption in Washington |url=https://malinowski.house.gov/media/press-releases/representative-malinowski-leads-fight-end-corruption-washington |website=Tom Malinowski Congressional Web Site |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Congressman Max Rose Press Release 2020.01.16\">{{cite web |title=10 Years After Disastrous Citizens United Decision, Rose, Porter, Freshmen Dems Launch New \u2018End Corruption\u2019 Caucus |url=https://maxrose.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=2450 |website=Max Rose Congressional Web Site |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===COVID-19===\nMalinowski joked during an April 2020 livestream with constituents that he would withhold shipments of [[Lysol]] disinfectant to the state of [[Kentucky]] until [[Senate Majority Leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]], relents in his opposition to Democrat-backed vote-by-mail measures amid the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]]. He was referring to a [[Reckitt Benckiser]] manufacturing plant located in [[Hillsborough Township, New Jersey|Hillsborough Township]] which produces 100% of the United States' supply of Lysol disinfectant.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Snowflack |first1=Fred |title=Kentucky Strikes Back at Malinowski |url=https://www.insidernj.com/kentucky-strikes-back-at-malinowski/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=Insider NJ |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Saxena |first1=Vivek |title=\u2018We make 100 percent\u2019: NJ Dem \u2018jokes\u2019 about withholding Lysol products to strongarm Mitch McConnell |url=https://www.bizpacreview.com/2020/04/10/we-make-100-percent-nj-dem-jokes-about-withholding-lysol-products-to-strongarm-mitch-mcconnell-906928 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=Biz Pac Review |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n\"There\u2019s nothing funny about a member of Congress threatening to withhold vital supplies from Kentuckians during a deadly outbreak,\u201d [[Republican Party of Kentucky]] spokesman Mike Lonergan said in response to the comments. \u201cAt a time when families and communities across the country are suffering, people are coming together to fight the coronavirus. This Democrat congressman\u2019s threats need and deserve to be condemned.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Creitz |first1=Charles |title=Democratic rep jokes about withholding Lysol shipments to Kentucky in swipe at McConnell |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/malinowski-jokes-withholding-lysol-shipments-kentucky-mcconnell |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=Fox News |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski added that this was a 'fantasy' of his that is unlikely actually work.\n\n===Illegal Immigrants===\nAt an August 2019 town hall, Malinowski told constituents that illegal immigrants are needed to mow \"our beautiful lawns\" and perform menial jobs rejected by tech-focused teenagers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ferrechio |first1=Susan |title=Democratic lawmaker: Illegal immigrants needed to mow 'our beautiful lawns' |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/congress/democratic-lawmaker-illegal-immigrants-needed-to-mow-our-beautiful-lawns |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Washington Examiner |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wulfsohn |first1=Joseph |title=Dem Rep. Tom Malinowski: We need illegal immigrants to 'mow our beautiful lawns' |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/dem-rep-tom-malinowski-illegal-immigrants-to-mow-lawns |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Fox News |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref> The comments made national headlines and drew backlash from critics who called Malinowski \"out of touch\". Questions were raised as to whether Malinowski pays illegal immigrants to mow his personal lawn.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moritz-Rabson |first1=Daniel |title=DEMOCRATIC CONGRESSMAN SAYS UNDOCUMENTED IMMIGRANTS ARE GOOD FOR 'MOWING OUR BEAUTIFUL LAWNS' |url=https://www.newsweek.com/democratic-congressman-says-undocumented-immigrants-are-good-mowing-our-beautiful-lawns-1455893 |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Newsweek |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Prince |first1=Molly |title=WATCH: Dem Lawmaker Says Illegal Immigrants Are Needed To Mow \u2018Our Beautiful Lawns\u2019 |url=https://www.dailywire.com/news/watch-dem-lawmaker-says-illegal-immigrants-are-molly-prince |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=The Daily Wire |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Meads |first1=Timothy |title=WATCH: Dem Lawmaker Says Illegal Immigrants Are Needed To Mow \u2018Our Beautiful Lawns\u2019 |url=New Jersey Democrat: We Need Illegals To Mow Our 'Beautiful Lawns'e |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Townhall |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Impeachment===\nMalinowski was the first member of the New Jersey congressional delegation to call to begin the impeachment inquiry of President [[Donald Trump]] in May 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moran |first1=Tom |title=Malinowski, the first Jersey House member to favor impeachment hearings, explains why|url=https://www.nj.com/opinion/2019/05/malinowski-the-first-jersey-house-member-to-favor-impeachment-hearings-explains-why-moran.html |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=NJ.com |date=May 29, 2019}}</ref> At the time, he was the only swing-district Democrat to support opening an impeachment inquiry into the President. Malinowski came under sharp criticism from constituents at subsequent town hall meetings as well as in press.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff |first1=The |title=Malinowski discovers vocal impeachment opposition at Branchburg town hall |url=https://savejersey.com/2019/12/malinowski-discovers-vocal-impeachment-opposition-at-branchburg-town-hall/ |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Save Jersey |date=December 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Parker-Maygar |first1=Alex |title=Malinowski talks impeachment at town hall as House vote looms |url=https://www.newjerseyhills.com/videos-malinowski-talks-impeachment-at-town-hall-as-house-vote/article_c3f3ed11-b7ff-5300-b051-24899abb62f2.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=New Jersey Globe |date=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMalinowski owns a home in [[Washington, D.C.]], and was registered to vote there as of March 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pizarro |first1=Max |title=Residency Question Hounds Malinowski on Eve of Union County Vote |url=https://www.insidernj.com/residency-question-hounds-malinowski-eve-union-county-vote/ |accessdate=16 July 2018 |publisher=InsiderNJ |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref> He began renting a home in [[Rocky Hill, New Jersey]], in September 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brodesser-Akner |first1=Claude |title=What's really going on with all these 'carpetbagger' political attacks in New Jersey? |url=https://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/07/hed_whats_really_going_on_with_all_these_carpetbag.html |accessdate=17 July 2018 |publisher=NJ.com |date=July 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pathe |first1=Simone |title=Could Past DC Residency Be Liability for Some Democrats? |url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/past-dc-residency-liability-democrats |accessdate=16 July 2018 |publisher=Roll Call |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski's stepfather [[Blair Clark]] was a journalist. Clark's sister was [[Anne Clark Martindell|Anne Martindell]], a member of the [[New Jersey State Senate]] (1974\u20131977) and a [[List of ambassadors of the United States to New Zealand|United States ambassador to New Zealand]] (1979\u20131981).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wildstein |first1=David |title=Malinowski and the residency thing |url=https://newjerseyglobe.com/section-2/malinowski-residency-thing/ |accessdate= August 8, 2018 |publisher=New Jersey Globe |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski has one daughter, Emily.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Muscavage |first1=Nick |title= NJ elections: Democrat Tom Malinowski unseats Republican Leonard Lance in NJ's 7th Congressional District  |url=https://www.mycentraljersey.com/story/news/politics/2018/11/07/nj-7th-district-congress-tom-malinowski-defeats-leonard-lance/1902521002/ |accessdate= March 3, 2020 |publisher= Courier News and Home News Tribune |date=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://malinowski.house.gov/ Congressman Tom Malinowski] official U.S. House website\n*[https://malinowskifornj.com/ Tom Malinowski for Congress]\n{{CongLinks|fec=H8NJ07223|votesmart=179645|congbio=M001203|congress=tom-malinowski/M001203}}\n\n{{Commons category|Tomasz P. Malinowski}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Posner (lawyer)|Michael Posner]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Virginia L. Bennett]]<br>{{small|Acting}}}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Leonard Lance]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from New Jersey|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Elaine Luria]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=383rd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ben McAdams]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Members of the U.S. House of Representatives}}\n{{NJ-FedRep}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malinowski, Tom}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Antony's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Human Rights Watch people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:New Jersey Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Princeton, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Rocky Hill, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from S\u0142upsk]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Princeton High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Assistant Secretaries of State]]\n[[Category:United States National Security Council staffers]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Progressivism in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Eraclientseasonalone", "label": "safe", "comment": "source added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Malinowski"}
{"title_page": "Attenborough, Nottinghamshire", "text_new": "{{short description|Village in Nottinghamshire, England}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n | static_image =         Attenborough parish church.jpg\n | static_image_width =         280px\n | static_image_caption = [[St. Mary's Church, Attenborough|Attenborough Parish Church]]\n | official_name=         Attenborough\n | country=               England\n | region=                East Midlands\n | population=            2,328\n | population_ref =       (Ward. 2011)\n | os_grid_reference=     SK 51782 34486\n | coordinates = {{coord|52.905|-1.230|display=it|format=dms}}\n |map_type =              Nottinghamshire\n | post_town=             NOTTINGHAM\n | postcode_area=         NG\n | postcode_district=     NG9\n | dial_code=             0115\n | constituency_westminster= [[Broxtowe (UK Parliament constituency)|Broxtowe]]\n | civil_parish=\n | shire_district= [[Borough of Broxtowe|Broxtowe]]\n | shire_county=[[Nottinghamshire]]\n }}\n'''Attenborough''' is a suburban village in the [[Borough of Broxtowe|Broxtowe]] borough of [[Nottinghamshire]], [[England]]. It forms part of [[Greater Nottingham]], and is {{convert|4 + 1/2|miles}} to the southwest of the city of [[Nottingham]], between [[Long Eaton]] (to the southwest) and [[Beeston, Nottinghamshire|Beeston]] (to the northeast). The population of the ward within the Borough of Broxtowe taken at the 2011 Census was 2,328.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=13694003&c=Attenborough&d=14&e=62&g=6456495&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=362&m=0&r=1&s=1459694801236&enc=1|title=Broxtowe ward population 2011|accessdate=3 April 2016|publisher = Office for National Statistics|work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref> It adjoins the suburbs of [[Toton]] to the west and [[Chilwell]] to the north.\n\nThe village is the location of [[Attenborough railway station]] and the [[Attenborough Nature Reserve]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.attenboroughnaturecentre.co.uk|title=Attenborough Nature Centre & Reserve|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\nAttenborough Nature Reserve is a series of [[gravel pit]]s, which were flooded after gravel extraction and are now a haven for birds and other wildlife.\n\nThe main commercial centre of Attenborough is around the junction of Nottingham Road (the [[A6005 road|A6005]]) and Attenborough Lane.\n\nNearer to the nature reserve is a tennis club, along with a private day-nursery,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.attenboroughdn.co.uk|title=Attenborough Day Nursery|publisher=}}</ref> which, in 2005, along with the Attenborough Prep School, was bought by [[Robert Everist]], who then sold the nursery and closed the 100-year-old school. In media coverage, it was claimed that Everist's company had pressured employees into handing in their notice a week before closing the company.<ref name=\"Directory\">{{cite web|title=Directory|url=http://directory007.blogspot.co.uk/2009/02/attenborough-preparatory-school.html|website=Directory Blog|accessdate=17 February 2009}}</ref> The [[Attenborough Cricket Club]] (which doubles as the [[village green]]) and [[St. Mary's Church, Attenborough|St. Mary's Church]] (a [[Church of England]] parish church).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://southwellchurches.nottingham.ac.uk/attenborough/hhistory.php|title=Attenborough - History|publisher=}}</ref> This southeastern part of Attenborough is bounded to the northwest by the railway line and on the other three sides by the wetlands of the nature reserve. It is the historic part of the village, with two [[listed building]]s and the listed church itself.<ref>[http://beestoncivicsociety.org.uk/gallery-1.html Beeston and District Civic Society] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812075138/http://beestoncivicsociety.org.uk/gallery-1.html |date=12 August 2011 }} Listed buildings</ref>\n\nIn 1944 a plot of land was given on Attenborough Lane by Mr E.V. Brown and Mr J.M. Barnett for a village hall, but it was not until 1955 when funds permitted that construction began. The building was designed by Lionel Thraves of Messrs. Thraves and Son of Nottingham and built by the contractor A.H. Taylor (Nottingham) Ltd. It was named the Lucy Brown Village Hall in memory of the late wife of Mr. E.V. Brown.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Village Hall at Attenborough |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0002507/19550924/057/0003 |newspaper=Long Eaton Advertiser |location=England |date=24 September 1955 |access-date=12 April 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription}}</ref> The cost of construction was \u00a38,200 ({{Inflation|UK|8200|1956|r=-2|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}).{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} The opening on 15 September 1956 was attended by Mr. V.H. Oade (vice-chairman of [[Beeston and Stapleford Urban District|Beeston and Stapleford Council]]) and [[Martin Redmayne, Baron Redmayne]] (M.P. for [[Rushcliffe (UK Parliament constituency)|Rushcliffe]]).<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=A New Centre of Village Life? M.P. and Council Vice-Chariman Present at Opening of Hall at Attenborough |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0002507/19560922/051/0003 |newspaper=Long Eaton Advertiser |location=England |date=22 September 1956 |access-date=12 April 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref>\n\nSome time ago{{When|date=September 2011}}, a hoard of [[Roman currency|Roman coins]] were found on the [[footpath (right of way)|footpath]] that runs over the railway and onto Barrett Lane.\n\n==Conservation areas==\nThere are two conservations areas which Broxtowe Borough Council has designated in Attenborough. These are Attenborough Village and Attenborough Barratt Lane.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.broxtowe.gov.uk/for-you/planning/conservation-areas/ |title=Conservation areas |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Broxtowe Borough Council |publisher=Broxtowe Borough Council |access-date=12 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n===Attenborough Village Conservation Area===\nThe conservation are comprises Church Lane, the north side of Shady Lane as far as Field House, The Strand and Sportsground and Attenborough Lane to its junction with Allendale Avenue.<ref>{{cite report |author= |author-link= |authors= |date= |title=Attenborough Village Conservation Area Character Appraisal |url=https://www.broxtowe.gov.uk/media/1902/attenborough-village-con-area-appraisal.pdf |publisher=Broxtowe Borough Council |page=12 |docket= |access-date=12 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref> The conservation area was established in June 1977.<ref name=LGA1980>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Arcadia Needs Keeping |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0002508/19801120/412/0007 |newspaper=Long Eaton Advertiser |location=England |date=20 November 1980 |access-date=12 April 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> Notable buildings include:\n[[File:House in Attenborough - geograph.org.uk - 1771052.jpg|thumb|Cloud House, Attenborough Lane]]\n[[File:House in Attenborough - geograph.org.uk - 1771054.jpg|thumb|The Orchards, Church Lane]]\n[[File:Thatched Cottage, Attenborough.jpg|thumb|Thatched Cottage, Church Lane]]\n*Hycroft. 202 Attenborough Lane\n*Cloud House. 233 Attenborough Lane\n*[[St. Mary's Church, Attenborough|St. Mary's Church]]. [[Grade I listed]]<ref>{{National Heritage List for England entry| num= 1263869 |desc=Church of St Mary the Virgin, Church Lane |grade=I |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> \n*The Orchards, 1 Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Blue Gate, Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Woodbine Cottage, 9 Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Red Ridges, Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Thatched Cottage, Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Croft Cottage. 13 Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Ireton House. 15 Church Lane, Attenborough [[Grade II listed]]<ref>{{National Heritage List for England entry| num= 1247991 |desc=Ireton House, Church Lane |grade=II |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> \n*Rothmere (formerly Glebe Croft). 17 Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Vale Cottage. 19 Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Field House Shady Lane\n*Long Acres, 25 Shady Lane\n*Rose Cottage, 45 The Strand, Attenborough. [[Grade II listed]]<ref>{{National Heritage List for England entry| num= 1263851 |desc=Rose Cottage, 45, The Strand |grade=II |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> \n*Brookside. 49 The Strand, Attenborough Architect [[John Rigby Poyser]]\n*The Willows, 51 The Strand, Attenborough. Architect [[John Rigby Poyser]]\n\n===Attenborough Barratt Lane Conservation Area===\nThe conservation area comprises the major part of Barratt Lane from number 23 to Attenborough Lane, Attenborough Lane from the level crossing to house number 201, and 1, 2 and 3 Long Lane.<ref>{{cite report |author= |author-link= |authors= |date= |title=Attenborough Barratt Lane Conservation Area Character Appraisal |url=https://www.broxtowe.gov.uk/media/1908/attenborough-barratt-ln-appraisal.pdf |publisher=Broxtowe Borough Council |page=11 |docket= |access-date=12 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref> The conservation area was established in November 1980.<ref name=LGA1980/> The first nine houses were built at the end of the nineteenth century along the south side of Barratt Lane and had their fronts facing the railway rather than the lane, offering fine views towards the church and the River Trent beyond. Notable buildings include:\n[[File:The Firs (geograph 6432522).jpg|thumb|The Firs, Barratt Lane]]\n*The Haven, 15 Barratt Lane\n*16 Barratt Lane. Architect H.H. Brittle 1937<ref>{{cite archive |first= |last= |item =1780 |item-url = |type = Building Plan Register |item-id =  |date = 1937 |page= |pages= |fonds = |series = |file = DC/BS/4/2/2 |box= |collection = District Council Records |collection-url = |repository = |institution =Nottinghamshire Archives Office |location = [[Nottingham]] |oclc= |accession= |ref=}}</ref>\n*17 Barratt Lane\n*18 Barratt Lane. Architect [[John Frederick Dodd]] 1936<ref>{{cite archive |first= |last= |item =1369 |item-url = |type = Building Plan Register |item-id =  |date = 1936 |page= |pages= |fonds = |series = |file = DC/BS/4/2/2 |box= |collection = District Council Records |collection-url = |repository = |institution =Nottinghamshire Archives Office |location = [[Nottingham]] |oclc= |accession= |ref=}}</ref>\n*The Firs, 19 Barratt Lane\n*Attenborough House 21 Barratt Lane.\n*Norfolk House, 1 Long Lane\n*2 Long Lane\n*3 Long Lane\n\n==Flood defences==\nThe village was flooded in November 2000. In 2006, plans were drawn up for substantial flood defences for the village. However, the scheme proved controversial because of the impact of a proposed high flood wall along The Strand. After a series of negotiations, planning permission was granted in August 2010, with the defences being moved to behind the village green. The work was completed in summer 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/pound-45m-flood-defences-used-time-safeguard-175/story-17446821-detail/story.html |title=\u00a345m flood defences used for first time to safeguard 175 homes across Notts |last=Britton |first=Alexander |date=November 28, 2012 |website=Nottingham Post |publisher=Local World. |access-date=April 8, 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Attenborough Nature Reserve Visitor Centre - geograph.org.uk - 763738.jpg |thumb|right|Attenborough Nature Centre]]\n\n==Local government and politics==\n{{see also|Broxtowe local elections}}\nAttenborough is an [[unparished area]] and has no parish council. For local government and [[election district|electoral]] purposes, Attenborough is one of the [[wards of the United Kingdom|wards]] within Broxtowe and returns one councillor to the borough council. In the [[2007 United Kingdom local elections|2007 local elections]], the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] won the seat.<ref>[http://www.broxtowe.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=549 Broxtowe Borough Council] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100731175057/http://www.broxtowe.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=549 |date=31 July 2010 }} Election results 2007\u201310 by ward</ref> For elections to Nottinghamshire County Council the village is covered by the [[electoral division]] of Beeston South & Attenborough (consisting of the Beeston Central, Beeston Rylands and Attenborough wards). [[2009 Nottinghamshire Council election|In 2009]], the Conservative candidate won the division.<ref>[http://www.nottinghamshire.gov.uk/home/your_council/councilelections/electionresultsbydivision09.htm?division=20#88 Nottinghamshire County Council] Beeston South & Attenborough election result 2009</ref>\n\nFor elections to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]], the village is part of the [[Broxtowe (UK Parliament constituency)|Broxtowe constituency]] for which the present [[Member for Parliament]] is [[Darren Henry]], for the Conservatives.\n\n==History==\nAttenborough was known in [[History of Anglo-Saxon England|Saxon]] times as ''Addensburgh''. It was the home village of [[Henry Ireton]] (1611 \u2013 26 November 1651), an English general in the army of [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] during the [[English Civil War]] and son-in-law of [[Oliver Cromwell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nottshistory.org.uk/whatnall1928/iretons_house.htm|title=Nottinghamshire history > Links with old Nottingham (1928): Attenborough: Ireton's House|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[First World War]], the railway station had its platforms extended as it was used as an interchange for soldiers heading for [[Chetwynd Barracks]]. During the [[Second World War]], the platforms were said to be the longest in Europe due to their proximity to the base.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n\nIn the graveyard of [[St. Mary's Church, Attenborough|St Mary's Church]], there is a memorial to the 134 people killed on 1 July 1918 in an explosion in the shell factory in nearby [[Chilwell]]. This death toll remains the largest number of deaths caused by a single explosion in mainland Britain.<ref>Maureen Rushton, Local Historian in her book \"The canary girls of Chilwell: the story of No. 6 Shell Filling Factory, Chilwell, Nottinghamshire\"</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Woollacott|first1=Angela|title=On Her Their Lives Depend: Munitions Workers in the Great War|url=https://archive.org/details/onhertheirlivesd0000wool|url-access=registration|date=1994|publisher=University of California Press|location=Oakland|isbn=978-0520085022|page=[https://archive.org/details/onhertheirlivesd0000wool/page/84 84]}}</ref>\n\nA ferry (''Barton Ferry'') used to cross the [[River Trent]] from the mouth of the [[River Erewash]] (near Attenborough) to [[Barton in Fabis]]. A crossing existed at this point since before 1774.<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Chapman\n  | first = John\n  | title = Map of Nottinghamshire\n  | year = 1774\n  | isbn = 0-902751-46-8}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nRoad transport is the primary method of transport in and out of the area which is connected to Nottingham by the A6005. [[East Midlands Airport]] is approximately {{convert|7 + 1/2|miles}} away; the airport serves domestic and international routes, focused mainly within Europe.\n\n===Bus===\nBus services operate to Nottingham, [[Derby]], Beeston, [[Stapleford, Nottinghamshire|Stapleford]], Long Eaton and other local towns.\n\n;[[Trent Barton]]\n:Indigo: Nottingham \u2013 QMC \u2013 University Boulevard \u2013 Beeston \u2013 Chilwell \u2013 Attenborough \u2013 Toton \u2013 Long Eaton - Spondon - Derby.\n\n:Skylink Nottingham: Nottingham - South Lenton - University Boulevard - South Beeston - Chilwell - Attenborough - Long Eaton - Sawley - East Midlands Airport - Loughborough/Coalville.\n\n===Rail===\n\n====Attenborough====\n{{main|Attenborough railway station}}\n\nAn hourly service is provided throughout the day by [[East Midlands Railway]] Matlock to Nottingham service. Additional services run at peak times, including some operated by [[CrossCountry]].\n\n====Beeston====\n[[Beeston railway station]] is approximately {{convert|1 + 1/2|miles}} away. It provides regular and direct connections to various locations across the United Kingdom.\n\n==Sport==\nThe village has its own non league football club, [[Attenborough F.C.]] founded in 1947, who currently play in the {{English football updater|Attenbor}} at the Strand.<ref>Paperblog: [https://en.paperblog.com/the-farewell-hop-1466959/ The Farewell Hop \u2013 Paperblog], accessdate: March 7, 2020</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n*[[Henry Ireton]] Roundhead General during the [[English Civil War]], and son-in-law to [[Oliver Cromwell]], born in Attenborough in 1611.\n*[[Sophia Di Martino]] actress in tv series including [[Flowers (TV series)|Flowers]], [[Friday Night Dinner]] and [[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]], born in Attenborough in 1983.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/nottingham/content/articles/2007/05/31/sophia_di_martino_interview_feature.shtml BBC Nottingham People - Sophia di Martino]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Attenborough, Nottinghamshire}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Nottinghamshire}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Nottinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Places in the Borough of Broxtowe]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Village in Nottinghamshire, England}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n | static_image =         Attenborough parish church.jpg\n | static_image_width =         280px\n | static_image_caption = [[St. Mary's Church, Attenborough|Attenborough Parish Church]]\n | official_name=         Attenborough\n | country=               England\n | region=                East Midlands\n | population=            2,328\n | population_ref =       (Ward. 2011)\n | os_grid_reference=     SK 51782 34486\n | coordinates = {{coord|52.905|-1.230|display=it|format=dms}}\n |map_type =              Nottinghamshire\n | post_town=             NOTTINGHAM\n | postcode_area=         NG\n | postcode_district=     NG9\n | dial_code=             0115\n | constituency_westminster= [[Broxtowe (UK Parliament constituency)|Broxtowe]]\n | civil_parish=\n | shire_district= [[Borough of Broxtowe|Broxtowe]]\n | shire_county=[[Nottinghamshire]]\n }}\n'''Attenborough''' is a suburban village in the [[Borough of Broxtowe|Broxtowe]] borough of [[Nottinghamshire]], [[England]]. It forms part of [[Greater Nottingham]], and is {{convert|4 + 1/2|miles}} to the southwest of the city of [[Nottingham]], between [[Long Eaton]] (to the southwest) and [[Beeston, Nottinghamshire|Beeston]] (to the northeast). The population of the ward within the Borough of Broxtowe taken at the 2011 Census was 2,328.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=13694003&c=Attenborough&d=14&e=62&g=6456495&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=362&m=0&r=1&s=1459694801236&enc=1|title=Broxtowe ward population 2011|accessdate=3 April 2016|publisher = Office for National Statistics|work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref> It adjoins the suburbs of [[Toton]] to the west and [[Chilwell]] to the north.\n\nThe village is the location of [[Attenborough railway station]] and the [[Attenborough Nature Reserve]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.attenboroughnaturecentre.co.uk|title=Attenborough Nature Centre & Reserve|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\nAttenborough Nature Reserve is a series of [[gravel pit]]s, which were flooded after gravel extraction and are now a haven for birds and other wildlife.\n\nThe main commercial centre of Attenborough is around the junction of Nottingham Road (the [[A6005 road|A6005]]) and Attenborough Lane.\n\nNearer to the nature reserve is a tennis club, along with a private day-nursery,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.attenboroughdn.co.uk|title=Attenborough Day Nursery|publisher=}}</ref> which, in 2005, along with the Attenborough Prep School, was bought by [[Robert Everist]], who then sold the nursery and closed the 100-year-old school. In media coverage, it was claimed that Everist's company had pressured employees into handing in their notice a week before closing the company.<ref name=\"Directory\">{{cite web|title=Directory|url=http://directory007.blogspot.co.uk/2009/02/attenborough-preparatory-school.html|website=Directory Blog|accessdate=17 February 2009}}</ref> The [[Attenborough Cricket Club]] (which doubles as the [[village green]]) and [[St. Mary's Church, Attenborough|St. Mary's Church]] (a [[Church of England]] parish church).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://southwellchurches.nottingham.ac.uk/attenborough/hhistory.php|title=Attenborough - History|publisher=}}</ref> This southeastern part of Attenborough is bounded to the northwest by the railway line and on the other three sides by the wetlands of the nature reserve. It is the historic part of the village, with two [[listed building]]s and the listed church itself.<ref>[http://beestoncivicsociety.org.uk/gallery-1.html Beeston and District Civic Society] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812075138/http://beestoncivicsociety.org.uk/gallery-1.html |date=12 August 2011 }} Listed buildings</ref>\n\nIn 1944 a plot of land was given on Attenborough Lane by Mr E.V. Brown and Mr J.M. Barnett for a village hall, but it was not until 1955 when funds permitted that construction began. The building was designed by Lionel Thraves of Messrs. Thraves and Son of Nottingham and built by the contractor A.H. Taylor (Nottingham) Ltd. It was named the Lucy Brown Village Hall in memory of the late wife of Mr. E.V. Brown.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Village Hall at Attenborough |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0002507/19550924/057/0003 |newspaper=Long Eaton Advertiser |location=England |date=24 September 1955 |access-date=12 April 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription}}</ref> The cost of construction was \u00a38,200 ({{Inflation|UK|8200|1956|r=-2|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}).{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} The opening on 15 September 1956 was attended by Mr. V.H. Oade (vice-chairman of [[Beeston and Stapleford Urban District|Beeston and Stapleford Council]]) and [[Martin Redmayne, Baron Redmayne]] (M.P. for [[Rushcliffe (UK Parliament constituency)|Rushcliffe]]).<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=A New Centre of Village Life? M.P. and Council Vice-Chariman Present at Opening of Hall at Attenborough |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0002507/19560922/051/0003 |newspaper=Long Eaton Advertiser |location=England |date=22 September 1956 |access-date=12 April 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref>\n\nSome time ago{{When|date=September 2011}}, a hoard of [[Roman currency|Roman coins]] were found on the [[footpath (right of way)|footpath]] that runs over the railway and onto Barrett Lane.\n\n==Conservation areas==\nThere are two conservations areas which Broxtowe Borough Council has designated in Attenborough. These are Attenborough Village and Attenborough Barratt Lane.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.broxtowe.gov.uk/for-you/planning/conservation-areas/ |title=Conservation areas |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Broxtowe Borough Council |publisher=Broxtowe Borough Council |access-date=12 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n===Attenborough Village Conservation Area===\nThe conservation are comprises Church Lane, the north side of Shady Lane as far as Field House, The Strand and Sportsground and Attenborough Lane to its junction with Allendale Avenue.<ref>{{cite report |author= |author-link= |authors= |date= |title=Attenborough Village Conservation Area Character Appraisal |url=https://www.broxtowe.gov.uk/media/1902/attenborough-village-con-area-appraisal.pdf |publisher=Broxtowe Borough Council |page=12 |docket= |access-date=12 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref> The conservation area was established in June 1977.<ref name=LGA1980>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Arcadia Needs Keeping |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0002508/19801120/412/0007 |newspaper=Long Eaton Advertiser |location=England |date=20 November 1980 |access-date=12 April 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> Notable buildings include:\n[[File:House in Attenborough - geograph.org.uk - 1771052.jpg|thumb|Cloud House, Attenborough Lane]]\n[[File:House in Attenborough - geograph.org.uk - 1771054.jpg|thumb|The Orchards, Church Lane]]\n[[File:Thatched Cottage, Attenborough.jpg|thumb|Thatched Cottage, Church Lane]]\n*Hycroft. 202 Attenborough Lane\n*Cloud House. 233 Attenborough Lane\n*[[St. Mary's Church, Attenborough|St. Mary's Church]]. [[Grade I listed]]<ref>{{National Heritage List for England entry| num= 1263869 |desc=Church of St Mary the Virgin, Church Lane |grade=I |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> \n*The Orchards, 1 Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Blue Gate, Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Woodbine Cottage, 9 Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Red Ridges, Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Thatched Cottage, Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Croft Cottage. 13 Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Ireton House. 15 Church Lane, Attenborough [[Grade II listed]]<ref>{{National Heritage List for England entry| num= 1247991 |desc=Ireton House, Church Lane |grade=II |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> \n*Rothmere (formerly Glebe Croft). 17 Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Vale Cottage. 19 Church Lane, Attenborough\n*Field House Shady Lane\n*Long Acres, 25 Shady Lane\n*Rose Cottage, 45 The Strand, Attenborough. [[Grade II listed]]<ref>{{National Heritage List for England entry| num= 1263851 |desc=Rose Cottage, 45, The Strand |grade=II |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> \n*Brookside. 49 The Strand, Attenborough Architect [[John Rigby Poyser]]\n*The Willows, 51 The Strand, Attenborough. Architect [[John Rigby Poyser]]\n\n===Attenborough Barratt Lane Conservation Area===\nThe conservation area comprises the major part of Barratt Lane from number 23 to Attenborough Lane, Attenborough Lane from the level crossing to house number 201, and 1, 2 and 3 Long Lane.<ref>{{cite report |author= |author-link= |authors= |date= |title=Attenborough Barratt Lane Conservation Area Character Appraisal |url=https://www.broxtowe.gov.uk/media/1908/attenborough-barratt-ln-appraisal.pdf |publisher=Broxtowe Borough Council |page=11 |docket= |access-date=12 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref> The conservation area was established in November 1980.<ref name=LGA1980/> The first nine houses were built at the end of the nineteenth century along the south side of Barratt Lane and had their fronts facing the railway rather than the lane, offering fine views towards the church and the River Trent beyond. Notable buildings include:\n[[File:The Firs (geograph 6432522).jpg|thumb|The Firs, Barratt Lane]]\n*The Haven, 15 Barratt Lane\n*16 Barratt Lane. Architect H.H. Brittle 1937<ref>{{cite archive |first= |last= |item =1780 |item-url = |type = Building Plan Register |item-id =  |date = 1937 |page= |pages= |fonds = |series = |file = DC/BS/4/2/2 |box= |collection = District Council Records |collection-url = |repository = |institution =Nottinghamshire Archives Office |location = [[Nottingham]] |oclc= |accession= |ref=}}</ref>\n*17 Barratt Lane\n*18 Barratt Lane. Architect [[John Frederick Dodd]] 1936<ref>{{cite archive |first= |last= |item =1369 |item-url = |type = Building Plan Register |item-id =  |date = 1936 |page= |pages= |fonds = |series = |file = DC/BS/4/2/2 |box= |collection = District Council Records |collection-url = |repository = |institution =Nottinghamshire Archives Office |location = [[Nottingham]] |oclc= |accession= |ref=}}</ref>\n*The Firs, 19 Barratt Lane\n*Attenborough House 21 Barratt Lane.\n*Norfolk House, 1 Long Lane\n*2 Long Lane\n*3 Long Lane\n\n==Flood defences==\nThe village was flooded in November 2000. In 2006, plans were drawn up for substantial flood defences for the village. However, the scheme proved controversial because of the impact of a proposed high flood wall along The Strand. After a series of negotiations, planning permission was granted in August 2010, with the defences being moved to behind the village green. The work was completed in summer 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/pound-45m-flood-defences-used-time-safeguard-175/story-17446821-detail/story.html |title=\u00a345m flood defences used for first time to safeguard 175 homes across Notts |last=Britton |first=Alexander |date=November 28, 2012 |website=Nottingham Post |publisher=Local World. |access-date=April 8, 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Attenborough nature reserve.jpg|thumb|right|Attenborough Nature Centre]]\n\n==Local government and politics==\n{{see also|Broxtowe local elections}}\nAttenborough is an [[unparished area]] and has no parish council. For local government and [[election district|electoral]] purposes, Attenborough is one of the [[wards of the United Kingdom|wards]] within Broxtowe and returns one councillor to the borough council. In the [[2007 United Kingdom local elections|2007 local elections]], the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] won the seat.<ref>[http://www.broxtowe.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=549 Broxtowe Borough Council] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100731175057/http://www.broxtowe.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=549 |date=31 July 2010 }} Election results 2007\u201310 by ward</ref> For elections to Nottinghamshire County Council the village is covered by the [[electoral division]] of Beeston South & Attenborough (consisting of the Beeston Central, Beeston Rylands and Attenborough wards). [[2009 Nottinghamshire Council election|In 2009]], the Conservative candidate won the division.<ref>[http://www.nottinghamshire.gov.uk/home/your_council/councilelections/electionresultsbydivision09.htm?division=20#88 Nottinghamshire County Council] Beeston South & Attenborough election result 2009</ref>\n\nFor elections to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]], the village is part of the [[Broxtowe (UK Parliament constituency)|Broxtowe constituency]] for which the present [[Member for Parliament]] is [[Darren Henry]], for the Conservatives.\n\n==History==\nAttenborough was known in [[History of Anglo-Saxon England|Saxon]] times as ''Addensburgh''. It was the home village of [[Henry Ireton]] (1611 \u2013 26 November 1651), an English general in the army of [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] during the [[English Civil War]] and son-in-law of [[Oliver Cromwell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nottshistory.org.uk/whatnall1928/iretons_house.htm|title=Nottinghamshire history > Links with old Nottingham (1928): Attenborough: Ireton's House|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[First World War]], the railway station had its platforms extended as it was used as an interchange for soldiers heading for [[Chetwynd Barracks]]. During the [[Second World War]], the platforms were said to be the longest in Europe due to their proximity to the base.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n\nIn the graveyard of [[St. Mary's Church, Attenborough|St Mary's Church]], there is a memorial to the 134 people killed on 1 July 1918 in an explosion in the shell factory in nearby [[Chilwell]]. This death toll remains the largest number of deaths caused by a single explosion in mainland Britain.<ref>Maureen Rushton, Local Historian in her book \"The canary girls of Chilwell: the story of No. 6 Shell Filling Factory, Chilwell, Nottinghamshire\"</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Woollacott|first1=Angela|title=On Her Their Lives Depend: Munitions Workers in the Great War|url=https://archive.org/details/onhertheirlivesd0000wool|url-access=registration|date=1994|publisher=University of California Press|location=Oakland|isbn=978-0520085022|page=[https://archive.org/details/onhertheirlivesd0000wool/page/84 84]}}</ref>\n\nA ferry (''Barton Ferry'') used to cross the [[River Trent]] from the mouth of the [[River Erewash]] (near Attenborough) to [[Barton in Fabis]]. A crossing existed at this point since before 1774.<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Chapman\n  | first = John\n  | title = Map of Nottinghamshire\n  | year = 1774\n  | isbn = 0-902751-46-8}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nRoad transport is the primary method of transport in and out of the area which is connected to Nottingham by the A6005. [[East Midlands Airport]] is approximately {{convert|7 + 1/2|miles}} away; the airport serves domestic and international routes, focused mainly within Europe.\n\n===Bus===\nBus services operate to Nottingham, [[Derby]], Beeston, [[Stapleford, Nottinghamshire|Stapleford]], Long Eaton and other local towns.\n\n;[[Trent Barton]]\n:Indigo: Nottingham \u2013 QMC \u2013 University Boulevard \u2013 Beeston \u2013 Chilwell \u2013 Attenborough \u2013 Toton \u2013 Long Eaton - Spondon - Derby.\n\n:Skylink Nottingham: Nottingham - South Lenton - University Boulevard - South Beeston - Chilwell - Attenborough - Long Eaton - Sawley - East Midlands Airport - Loughborough/Coalville.\n\n===Rail===\n\n====Attenborough====\n{{main|Attenborough railway station}}\n\nAn hourly service is provided throughout the day by [[East Midlands Railway]] Matlock to Nottingham service. Additional services run at peak times, including some operated by [[CrossCountry]].\n\n====Beeston====\n[[Beeston railway station]] is approximately {{convert|1 + 1/2|miles}} away. It provides regular and direct connections to various locations across the United Kingdom.\n\n==Sport==\nThe village has its own non league football club, [[Attenborough F.C.]] founded in 1947, who currently play in the {{English football updater|Attenbor}} at the Strand.<ref>Paperblog: [https://en.paperblog.com/the-farewell-hop-1466959/ The Farewell Hop \u2013 Paperblog], accessdate: March 7, 2020</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n*[[Henry Ireton]] Roundhead General during the [[English Civil War]], and son-in-law to [[Oliver Cromwell]], born in Attenborough in 1611.\n*[[Sophia Di Martino]] actress in tv series including [[Flowers (TV series)|Flowers]], [[Friday Night Dinner]] and [[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]], born in Attenborough in 1983.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/nottingham/content/articles/2007/05/31/sophia_di_martino_interview_feature.shtml BBC Nottingham People - Sophia di Martino]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Attenborough, Nottinghamshire}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Nottinghamshire}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Nottinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Places in the Borough of Broxtowe]]\n", "name_user": "Palmiped", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFlood defences:change image", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attenborough,_Nottinghamshire"}
